cles. After just four months, it had $1 million in revenue and it eventually signed up more than 400 luxury-car owners. But HiGear collected just 30% of the fee, or roughly $90 per sale on average, and gave car owners the remaining 70%. And just to acquire a single paying customer cost HiGear roughly $300 in online ads. \"It would have been cheaper for us to buy 100 luxury cars and rent them out like a traditional car-rental service,\" he said. '),(133192727,13386262,'  WSJD is the Journal\'s home for tech news, analysis and product reviews. '),(133192728,13386262,'After an organized-crime ring used stolen credit cards and fake identities in December 2011 to bypass HiGear\'s security checks and steal four cars worth about $400,000 total, Mr. Moiz shut the startup down rather than face higher security and insurance costs. '),(133192729,13386262,'Neighborrow.com would let people list household items for rent, such as vacuum cleaners, hammers and food mixers. But co-founder                                                                        Adam Berk                                                                of New York concluded that \"you\'re never in an emergency where you need a power drill or you\'ll die.\" He pulled the plug on Neighborrow.com in 2011, after a five-year run.'),(133192730,13386262,'Some successful sharing-startup entrepreneurs say they find they must spend heavily on customer service. '),(133192731,13386262,'DogVacay.com, a two-year-old Los Angeles-based service that matches pet owners with pet sitters, spends about half of its operating budget on having 30 of its 52 employees provide 24/7 customer support, according to co-founder                                                                        Aaron Hirschhorn.                                                                The startup has raised $22 million from investors such as Benchmark and Andreessen Horowitz. It lets sitters charge their own rates, on average $30 a pet per day. The company takes a 15% cut.'),(133192732,13386262,'\"We work with recruiters to find people who aren\'t even looking for jobs,\" Mr. Hirschhorn said, such as retired veterinarian technicians and others who have experience working with animals. They need to be able to answer customers\' questions at any time, day or night, like what to do if you\'re looking after a dog that breaks through two childproof locks to wolf down an entire cooked turkey neck—a real example of an incident that recently took place at a sitter\'s home near Kalamazoo, Mich. '),(133192733,13386262,'DogVacay has a $3 million liability policy that covers up to $25,000 of vet coverage for every pet in a sitter\'s home, including his or her own. Mr. Hirschhorn said the coverage has come in handy, such as a few months ago when a 4-month-old Bernese Mountain Dog staying with a sitter near Washington, D.C., became ill from swallowing two pairs of socks and a pair of boxer shorts. The pup\'s surgery bill: $6,000.'),(133192734,13386262,'There also may be regulatory issues, including city laws that prevent people from renting out their apartments to strangers, or charging customers for rides. Uber\'s services are banned outright in New Orleans, Miami and Portland, Oregon. Uber and Airbnb also face mounting opposition from more conventional industry groups, like hoteliers, taxi drivers and brick-and-mortar retailers. '),(133192735,13386262,'\"There are cities that have, at the behest of incumbent transportation providers, imposed anti-consumer regulations intended to protect more expensive, slower and less reliable options,\" said Uber spokesman                                                                        Lane Kasselman.                                                                \"This is an evolving industry and we\'re working with decision makers in government and communities around the world to educate them on the competitive, economic and safety benefits of the Uber platform,\" he added. '),(133192736,13386262,'Airbnb has about five employees who are dedicated to educating government officials world-wide on how it works and answering any questions they might have, said                                                                        David Hantman,                                                                head of global public policy for the San Francisco-based company, which was started in 2008. Of the 35,000 cities in which Airbnb operates, only three have serious concerns about it—San Francisco, New York and Barcelona—he said, adding that the startup is working with officials in those areas to come to a resolution.'),(133192737,13386262,' Write to Sarah E. Needleman at sarah.needleman@wsj.com and Angus Loten at angus.loten@wsj.com '),(133192738,13386263,'ESPOO, Finland—\"Angry Birds\" has been downloaded billions of times, but will gamers still want to fling birds at a stack of malevolent pigs in a few years?'),(133192739,13386263,'Angry Birds\' maker, Rovio Entertainment Ltd., wants to prove that its flagship game has legs—or, rather, wings—but sluggish revenue growth and steep profit declines suggest that won\'t be easy. New games, such as \"Angry Birds Go!,\" haven\'t caught on, and talk of an initial public offering by Rovio executives has ceased.'),(133192740,13386263,'Rovio Chief Executive                                                                        Mikael Hed                                                                is overhauling the Finnish company\'s game revenue model, making downloads free and charging users for purchases made in the games. He is also expanding the company\'s entertainment business, gambling on a movie based on Angry Birds characters that is being financed and produced by Rovio, with distribution by Sony Pictures Entertainment. The film, due out in 2016, will test the company\'s staying power.'),(133192741,13386263,'Mr. Hed, 38 years old, says Angry Birds will prove as timeless as Dumbo. In a recent interview, he spoke about Rovio\'s plans for restarting growth and why game makers should cheer \"Flappy Bird,\" a low-tech game that garnered millions of fans overnight. '),(133192742,13386263,'Inspired by the success of Flappy Bird, Rovio just launched Retry, a simplistic flight simulator with retro visuals, based on Flappy Bird\'s tap-and-fly gameplay. The Rovio game was quietly launched on a few markets this week. '),(133192743,13386263,'Edited excerpts:'),(133192744,13386263,''),(133192745,13386263,' WSJ: Rovio has expanded beyond games into Angry Birds cartoons, theme parks and merchandise. What exactly does Rovio want to be?'),(133192746,13386263,' Mr. Hed: Rovio wants to be an entertainment company. Period. That\'s what we are. We started with games, mobile games specifically. Still, that is our strongest business. But we are also very strong in other areas that are typical for entertainment companies, like animation and consumer products.'),(133192747,13386263,''),(133192748,13386263,' WSJ: The breakneck growth you logged in the past few years has come to an end. Why?'),(133192749,13386263,' Mr. Hed: We\'re doing a big transition into the free-to-play business model, from a paid game company.'),(133192750,13386263,'The game space is really what makes all the difference for us, and that\'s where the biggest hits and misses are. For us, last year was one where we released strong titles, but perhaps fewer than we first estimated. Also, the free-to-play transition has taken longer than we anticipated. This year we\'re fully into the free-to-play model and there\'s been a huge shift in the whole mind-set of the company.'),(133192751,13386263,''),(133192752,13386263,' WSJ: Rovio started small and now employs 800 people. How have you managed that growth?'),(133192753,13386263,' Mr. Hed: It\'s been interesting from a CEO\'s standpoint. We\'ve made lots of changes in the organization. The games operation, for instance, used to be run by one person, essentially a small management team running the entire unit. As it started to grow—now it\'s 300 people—that centralized management didn\'t work.'),(133192754,13386263,'  WSJD is the Journal\'s home for tech news, analysis and product reviews. '),(133192755,13386263,'We\'ve divided these up into smaller, more independent studios, we call them tribes. Each tribe has their own [profit and loss sheet], their own management, their own targets, and they all focus on different types of products.'),(133192756,13386263,''),(133192757,13386263,' WSJ: What are your fast-growing peers—for example, Supercell, maker of \"Clash of Clans\"—doing that Rovio isn\'t?'),(133192758,13386263,' Mr. Hed: Supercell\'s success shows the opportunity in gaming industry. It\'s also a display of the brutal reality of how few [game makers] will make billions in profit. There is space for two or three [companies] at a time.'),(133192759,13386263,'If we want credible and sustainable growth, we need to diversify, to take some actions so that we don\'t build all of our existence purely on the assumption that everything we do will become a hit.'),(133192760,13386263,''),(133192761,13386263,' WSJ: What does the success of a low-tech game like \"Flappy Bird,\" created by a 20-something programmer in his spare time, say about the games industry and consumers?'),(133192762,13386263,' Mr. Hed: Flappy Bird was an interesting case study. Despite very simple game mechanics, a game can quickly snowball into a phenomenon. Even though you\'ve got incumbents in the industry, there\'s still the possibility that somebody comes from the left field, a guy in the garage, and does something interesting.'),(133192763,13386263,'Game production values are rising, which is great for the fans, but games like Flappy Bird show that it\'s not always a requirement for a game to be extremely expensive to make for it to succeed.'),(133192764,13386263,''),(133192765,13386263,' WSJ: One of your upcoming games is Stella, a female iteration of the Angry Birds franchise. Will women go for a game marketed to them?'),(133192766,13386263,' Mr. Hed: Lots of our fans are women and girls, but we felt we haven\'t been able to always serve them enough. We introduced Stella as an ancillary character and since, it has taken a life of its own. There has been a strong demand in retailers \'for anything to do with Stella\' so of course it was a natural step.'),(133192767,13386263,''),(133192768,13386263,' WSJ: What\'s happening with the Angry Birds movie? '),(133192769,13386263,' Mr. Hed: It\'s the largest individual investment that we\'ve ever made, yet it is the one that I don\'t ever lose any sleep over. It is just tremendously strong as a story. Every time I see the next iteration that the team has come up with, it just fills me with confidence that this is going to be quite huge. So that\'s what\'s coming up in 2016.'),(133192770,13386263,''),(133192771,13386263,' WSJ: Can you guarantee its success? Will an Angry Birds movie be watched a decade from now?'),(133192772,13386263,' Mr. Hed: Yes, I will go out on a limb on that. I believe so strongly in my movie.'),(133192773,13386263,' Write to Juhana Rossi at juhana.rossi@wsj.com and Sven Grundberg at sven.grundberg@wsj.com '),(133192774,13386264,'                                                                          Symantec Corp.                                   SYMC +0.64%                                      Symantec Corp.                                   U.S.: Nasdaq                                                $20.35                                                +0.13                 +0.64%                                                        May 8, 2014 2:12 pm                                 Volume (Delayed 15m)                 :                   3.05M                                                                                                       P/E Ratio                 16.30                                       Market Cap             $13.98 Billion                                                                   Dividend Yield               2.94%                                        Rev. per Employee               $316,233                                                                                                                                   05/04/14 Symantec Develops New Attack o...             04/15/14 CFO Moves: Brightstar, Popeyes...             04/08/14 Symantec Models Industry Risk ...             More quote details and news »                                                             SYMC in                                                                                                                          Your Value                 Your Change                                                                                                                                                                 Short position                                                                                                                    invented commercial antivirus software to protect computers from hackers a quarter-century ago. Now the company says such tactics are doomed to failure.'),(133192775,13386264,'Antivirus \"is dead,\" says Brian Dye, Symantec\'s senior vice president for information security. \"We don\'t think of antivirus as a moneymaker in any way.\"'),(133192776,13386264,'Antivirus products aim to prevent hackers from getting into a computer. But hackers often get in anyway these days. So Mr. Dye is leading a reinvention effort at Symantec that reflects a broader shift in the $70 billion a year cybersecurity industry.'),(133192777,13386264,'Rather than fighting to keep the bad guys out, new technologies from an array of companies assume hackers get in so aim to spot them and minimize the damage.'),(133192778,13386264,'  WSJD is the Journal\'s home for tech news, analysis and product reviews. '),(133192779,13386264,'Network-equipment maker                           