eally want to come out of the envelope one day is a piece of hardware that pushes both Airs together without compromise. Yes, that means a super-slim machine with a touch screen, some sort of keyboard, 4G connectivity and multi-day battery life. But I want other features, too, that can liberate us from the ways we interacted with computers in the PC era.'),(133192812,13386265,'How about Siri, managing email on our phones and laptops? Gesture control to manipulate on-screen objects with a wave of the hand? Wireless or even solar power, so I can ditch the charger? Connection ports disappearing altogether, as everything goes wireless and up into the cloud?'),(133192813,13386265,'That all may sound crazy, but so did the original Air. Now look how normal it seems.'),(133192814,13386265,'—Write to Joanna at joanna.stern@wsj.com and at @joannastern on Twitter. '),(133192815,13386266,'How do you stop a robot uprising?'),(133192816,13386266,'Shag carpeting.'),(133192817,13386266,''),(133192818,13386266,'Domestic robots may be in our future, but fluffy flooring is still Kryptonite to the first automated helpers that many of us have invited into our homes: robot vacuum cleaners.'),(133192819,13386266,'That\'s just one of the disappointments I discovered when I tried to find out whether robot vacuums can actually clean. A dozen years after the first Roomba robo-vacs made their debuts, today\'s models top out at $700 and tout improved power and navigation. One even has the same technology found in                                                                          Google\'s                                   GOOGL +0.64%                                      Google Inc. Cl A                                   U.S.: Nasdaq                                                $521.30                                                +3.30                 +0.64%                                                        May 8, 2014 2:13 pm                                 Volume (Delayed 15m)                 :                   1.77M                                                                                                       P/E Ratio                 28.46                                       Market Cap             $346.68 Billion                                                                   Dividend Yield               N/A                                       Rev. per Employee               $1,281,680                                                                                                                                   05/08/14 The Daily Startup: Full Speed ...             05/08/14 The Morning Download: SAP Lose...             05/07/14 How I Built It: Startup Takes ...             More quote details and news »                                                             GOOGL in                                                                                                                          Your Value                 Your Change                                                                                                                                                                 Short position                                                                                                                    self-driving cars.'),(133192820,13386266,'I lined up three of the latest—the $700                                                                          iRobot                                                                               Roomba 880, $600 Neato BotVac 85 and $500 Moneual Rydis H68 Pro—to test in my home and in the Journal Thunderdome, a pen I built to compare performance. On shag, medium-pile and low office carpet, I made them gobble Cheerios, M&Ms, beach sand—even potting soil.'),(133192821,13386266,'The result: None of the robots are good enough to replace a manual vacuum. The idea of a robo-cleaner may appeal to slackers, but just keeping one running is hard work. At best, they\'re a pricey supplement to clean homes with a lot of pet hair or dust, and best used between regular vacuuming.'),(133192822,13386266,'All of them were stymied by 1-inch shag, and none could muster the suction needed to pull sand out of medium-pile carpet. Just hunting for dust bunnies, all the bots got tangled up in power cables and caught in furniture.'),(133192823,13386266,'Today, some 15% of world-wide vacuum sales are bots, according to industry researchers. But let\'s be honest about why many of us get these little fellas: They\'re adorable. Watching one auto-navigate its way out of a tight corner is like watching a puppy climb stairs. I understand the compulsion to name them and dress them up in outfits.'),(133192824,13386266,'Snap out of it, people. None of these robots perform like Rosie from \"The Jetsons.\" If you spill Cheerios on the floor, just grab a vacuum and clean it up yourself. While robots will one day get intelligence to spot messes from afar, the ones I tested don\'t have it.'),(133192825,13386266,'Robot-makers have two approaches for how to navigate a floor. A Roomba bumps around in a seemingly random pattern, on the assumption that it will cover every spot at least three times. It gets help from sensors that guide it around walls and away from stairs, and suggest it linger when it sees, or even hears, extra dirt below. '),(133192826,13386266,'BotVac and Rydis are like Roomba\'s obsessive cousins. They use sensors to map out a room and then methodically follow a path to cover it. BotVac uses a proprietary laser scanner and navigation technology like in driverless cars to clean the house in 15-foot-by-15-foot chunks. '),(133192827,13386266,'Neither approach is perfect. In my tests with Cheerios and M&Ms sprinkled across carpets, none of the robots managed to scoop every morsel. The D-shaped BotVac has the most powerful vacuum and largest dust bin, but got confused and frequently ignored whole sections of my carpeted test pen. Rydis, which has the least effective vacuum and smallest bin, chewed up the Cheerios like Cookie Monster—leaving behind a bigger mess. (A Moneual spokesman said Cheerios are a little too large for its vacuum, and its prime targets are dust and hair.)'),(133192828,13386266,'Roomba and BotVac proved equally effective at finding chunks of food on low office carpet. In 45 minutes, they gobbled up 2 cups of Cheerios, leaving only a bit behind. But if you were relying on either to clean, who knows how long those missed Os might remain on your floor?'),(133192829,13386266,'Sand revealed a second problem: None of these robots have sufficient suction. I poured 4 ounces of sand onto fresh 5-foot-by-7-foot carpets, and no robot could retrieve even an ounce in 45 minutes. Letting them run longer yielded little additional sand. The companies say their bots can carry only a fraction of the suction power of a plugged in upright vacuum. \"Robot vacuums are a supplemental accessory, used to lengthen the time between serious vacuums,\" a Moneual spokesman said.'),(133192830,13386266,'And then there\'s the shag. The robots would stagger, seize up or report unseen obstructions. An iRobot spokeswoman said no robot vac is \"ideal on higher pile or shag carpets.\" The other makers echoed that sentiment—but none of them strongly emphasize on their websites, packaging or manuals that they don\'t work on this very common floor covering.'),(133192831,13386266,'Roomba and Rydis fared better on medium-pile area rugs, but BotVac even disappointed there: Its wheels would slip, rendering the BotVac\'s laser-guided smarts irrelevant.'),(133192832,13386266,' Welcome to   Personal Tech, the Journal\'s new home for personal tech review and news. '),(133192833,13386266,'A Neato spokeswoman said that the carpet I used for the test—a budget area rug from                                                                          Home Depot                                   HD +0.05%                                      Home Depot Inc.                                   U.S.: NYSE                                                $77.12                                                +0.04                 +0.05%                                                        May 8, 2014 2:13 pm                                 Volume (Delayed 15m)                 :                   3.44M                                                                                                       P/E Ratio                 20.48                                       Market Cap             $105.45 Billion                                                                   Dividend Yield               2.43%                                        Rev. per Employee               $215,923                                                                                                                                   05/04/14 Share Repurchases Boost PowerS...             04/16/14 Home Depot Lumbers Into E-Comm...             04/16/14 Home Depot Joins the Shale Rus...             More quote details and news »                                                             HD in                                                                                                                          Your Value                 Your Change                                                                                                                                                                 Short position                                                                                                                   —was made of waxy fibers that caused BotVac to lose grip. Whose fault is that? (The robot performed better on office carpet and hardwood.)'),(133192834,13386266,'These robot vacuums perform best with lightweight cleaning in spaces where the main culprits are dust and hair. All three bots were able to find an embarrassing volume of dust bunnies on the hardwood floors in my \"clean\" house.'),(133192835,13386266,'Because they\'re short, they can generally find their way under sofas and beds to places few people remember to reach with regular vacuums. They can be scheduled and they charge themselves, so emptying their tiny bins is all they ask of you.'),(133192836,13386266,'But they got themselves into enough trouble in one week in my house that I\'d feel uneasy about letting them run unattended. Roomba chewed up paper it found and managed to lodge itself under a chair. Rydis became unresponsive to controls, trying to push into a wall. And the particularly aggressive BotVac gobbled up an errant phone cable it found under a sofa—and pulled another gadget off a shelf by grabbing its cord. The companies say owners get used to prepping their houses to be robot friendly. \"People need to partner with their robots,\" a Neato spokeswoman said.'),(133192837,13386266,'If your house is clutter-free, these robots may do OK, especially if you set up virtual guardrails. But sorry, I don\'t have time to clean up my house before they do.'),(133192838,13386266,'If I were to choose a robot to zap dust bunnies in my own house, I\'d pick the Roomba for its balance of performance and floor-type adaptability. But at $700, that\'s one pricey dustbuster. The more basic Roomba 630 sells for half the price, though its brushes aren\'t as good at handling long hair.'),(133192839,13386266,'I look forward to a time when robot vacuum cleaners are as effective as their upright ancestors. At that point, I will buy one—and probably dress it up as a turtle. But that future has still not arrived.'),(133192840,13386266,' Write to Geoffrey A. Fowler at geoffrey.fowler@wsj.com '),(133192841,13386267,' Q: While decluttering my closet, I came across a stash of old notebook computers that I\'d like to get rid of but whose files I\'d like to copy first. Sadly, I don\'t have the power cords anymore. What should I do? '),(133192842,13386267,' A: You can usually find chargers for old laptops on                                                                          eBay.                                                                               But if you have a lot of machines to go through, it might be easier to remove the laptops\' hard drives and connect them to your existing computer via USB.'),(133192843,13386267,'The approach requires you to unscrew your laptop case (you\'ll need a small screwdriver), but don\'t be intimidated. For many computers, the process isn\'t difficult, and once you get the hang of it, you can help friends and family in the same predicament. '),(133192844,13386267,'This is also worth trying with an old laptop that won\'t start up; as long as its hard drive isn\'t broken, you\'ll be able to copy the files. Here\'s what to do:'),(133192845,13386267,' Remove your laptop\'s hard drive. This is usually as simple as unfastening a few screws and sliding the drive out (it\'s a thin metal box), but the exact steps vary for each model. A quick Web search will most likely turn up detailed instructions that a friendly techie has posted online (bless their hearts!). Note that some laptops, like first-gen MacBook Pros,are harder to get into than others, and may require a special screwdriver. If the steps look scary, ask a neighborhood tween for help. '),(133192846,13386267,' Connect the old drive to your existing computer. I use a dock called the Thermaltake BlacX for this. Plug it into your computer\'s USB port, then pop an old laptop drive into the dock to read and copy the files. '),(133192847,13386267,'The only hitch is that the dock might not be compatible with some older laptop drives (those made before 2007 or so). If you have ancient computers, the Sabrent USB-DSC9 cable should do the trick (and, like the dock, it works with PCs and Macs). This handy adapter connects to both older and current drives, and it takes up less space than the BlacX dock. Here\'s hoping your old journals aren\'t too embarrassing to revisit.'),(133192848,13386267,' Q: I somehow have thousands of duplicate photos on my Mac. Please tell me there\'s a way to get rid of them besides deleting them one by one. I don\'t have enough years left for that.  '),(133192849,13386267,' —Looking for a tech solution to a lifestyle problem? Email us: thefixer@wsj.com  '),(133192850,13386267,' A: There are several programs that scan your Mac for duplicate files. They\'ll even find identical photos, music files and documents that have different names—like a photo from your kid\'s birthday called \"IMG_0049.JPG\" in one folder and \"smooshcake.jpg\" in another.'),(133192851,13386267,'I use a program called \"Gemini,\" which costs $10, but I found similar apps that are currently on sale. For example, \"The Duplicate Finder\" is $3 until May 10, and \"Duplicate Detective\" is the same price until July 1. All are available in the Mac App Store.'),(133192852,13386268,'As soon as an email arrives on my iPhone that requires more than just a basic \"yes,\" \"no\" or \"OK, thanks,\" my Pavlovian response is to reach for my laptop.'),(133192853,13386268,'Our smartphones have come a long way over the past few years but the email apps they come with still don\'t have the functionality of desktop or Web-based email. I can\'t share my schedule, attach files, toggle between a new message and my inbox, or create follow-up reminders—at least not without dedicating real brain and thumb power to the cause. '),(133192854,13386268,''),(133192855,13386268,''),(133192856,13386268,'And I\'m not alone in thinking this is one of the greatest problems of our time. From Hop to Tipbit to Gusto, there are nearly as many short, quirkily named startups as letters in the alphabet that are all trying to liberate email. New options seem to arrive as fast as those unread messages. Just last Thursday another promising service called Acompli hit                                                                          Apple\'s                                   AAPL +0.21%                                      Apple Inc.                                   U.S.: Nasdaq                                                $590.25                                                +1.21                 +0.21%                                                        May 8, 2014 2:02 pm                                 Volume (Delayed 15m)                 :                   5.20M                                                                                                       P/E Ratio                 14.03                                       Market Cap             $510.22 Billion                                                                   Dividend Yield               2.23%                                        Rev. per Employee               $2,187,330                                                                                                                                   05/08/14 Data Point: There Are Hundreds...             05/07/14 Apple\'s North American Sales H...             05/07/14 Katie Cotton, Apple\'s Vice Pre...             More quote details and news »                                                             AAPL in                                                                                                                          Your Value                 Your Change                                                                                                                                                                 Short position                                                                                                                    App Store.'),(133192857,13386268,'So I set out to stock my iPhone and Android home screens with free email apps and explored them for features I want in a mobile inbox. No single app addressed all of my problems, but CloudMagic and Mailbox do a far better job than the default iOS and Android mail apps at putting desktop-quality email controls in my pocket. '),(133192858,13386268,'The first thing I want from an email app is a smarter \"New Message\" experience. I yearn to attach files, include my calendar availability, even check my inbox while working on a draft message—without jumping to different folders and apps. '),(133192859,13386268,'Here\'s an unsolved mystery: Why doesn\'t the iPhone email app have a file attachment button? Even apps like Mailbox, CloudMagic, Evomail and MyMail (which are available on Android) have simple attachment tools. The Acompli iPhone app goes even further.'),(133192860,13386268,' Welcome to   Personal Tech, the Journal\'s new home for personal tech review and news. '),(133192861,13386268,'From within the compose window, you can add recently emailed files and photos from your library, and even your location and the times you\'re available to connect. The app integrates your Gmail or Exchange calendar, so you simply tap on free blocks in your schedule to include them in your message.'),(133192862,13386268,'(Whether these companies store your passwords depends on the email provider you use, but when you give them access to your mail, they do store the contents on their servers. While not necessarily a privacy concern, it is at least a possible point of weakness you should know about.)'),(133192863,13386268,'Something none of these apps has mastered is draft messages. I often start to work on an email and then have to go back to search my inbox for more information, in the process losing the message in an inconvenient drafts folder.'),(133192864,13386268,'Evomail\'s Android app allows you to access drafts by simply holding down the compose button, but the feature is left out of the iPhone app, and both apps feel incomplete compared with the others. Disappointingly, better apps including Mailbox and CloudMagic don\'t have a drafts option at all—you completely lose your message if you exit the window.'),(133192865,13386268,'The second thing I want is to be able to easily file emails and then get back to them when I actually have time to respond.'),(133192866,13386268,'This is what Dropbox\'s popular Mailbox app, which is available for the iPhone and Android, is all about. You can swipe a message to the left to add it to a to-do list or have the app remind you about an email at a later time.'),(133192867,13386268,'And since Mailbox is soon coming (in limited release beta) to Mac computers, you\'ll be able to \"snooze\" a message on your phone, then grab it when you\'re at your desk. The downside? Mailbox only works with Gmail and Apple iCloud accounts.'),(133192868,13386268,'CloudMagic, on the other hand, is available for Android and iPhone, supports multiple email providers including Microsoft\'s corporate Exchange accounts, and has similar message reminders. '),(133192869,13386268,'But even more unique is CloudMagic\'s \"card\" feature. It scans messages and suggests saving specific content to different apps. For instance, you can save an article to read later in an app such as Pocket, or drop an important to-do item right into Evernote. It\'s convenient and works very well.'),(133192870,13386268,'CloudMagic also trumps the others at email search. Type in a term at the top of the inbox and it quickly searches the full text of all your messages from the beginning of time. Anyone who has ever been frustrated by the iPhone\'s slow and clumsy email search can appreciate that. And for being the world\'s most popular search company, Google still hasn\'t gotten its email search act together either. '),(133192871,13386268,'Other new apps concentrate on making it easier to find not text but photos and attachments. An app called Gusto, which for now only works with Gmail on the iPhone, creates a tab for each kind of attachment. You sift through all the photos people have sent you on one page, and documents and PDFs on another. Acompli offers the same functionality. '),(133192872,13386268,'No single app has yet fixed mobile email, but bit by bit they are helping to unshackle us from our computers. If this were a make-your-own-sundae situation, I\'d start with Mailbox\'s reminders and CloudMagic\'s search, throw in Evomail\'s draft tool, then top it off with Acompli\'s incredibly convenient calendar integration.'),(133192873,13386268,'Until that perfect app arrives, I\'ve replaced my iPhone and Android email apps with CloudMagic. It\'s the best overall option, with its reminders, improved search, cross-app cooperation and support for many email providers. But I\'m still keeping my laptop close by.'),(133192874,13386268,'—Write to Joanna Stern at joanna.stern@wsj.com and at @joannastern on Twitter.'),(133192875,13386269,'Meksikoa on vavisuttanut voimakas maanjäristys. Järistys oli voimakkuudeltaan 6.8 Richtertin asteikolla. Se tapahtui Meksiko Cityn eteläpuolella, 13 kilometrin päässä Tecpan de Galeanan kaupungista.'),(133192876,13386270,'Entinen pääministeri palkittiin SDP:n puoluekokouksessa Seinäjoella Väinö Tanner -mitalilla.'),(133192877,13386270,'Lipponen sanoo Ylelle, että kokoomus on johtajiensa kautta jättänyt vastuun.'),(133192878,13386270,'- On röyhkeätä ja uskomatonta, että pääministeri Jyrki Katainen ottaa lähtiessään kantaa Naton puolesta, Lipponen jyrähti.'),(133192879,13386270,'Jyrki Katainen on kertonut julkisuudessa, että haluaisi Suomen liittyvän Natoon. Viimeksi hän sanoi asiasta keskiviikkona Ylen vaalitentissä.'),(133192880,13386270,'Entisen pääministerin mielestä Suomessa ei arvosteta vastuunkantoa, vaan \"kaikenlaista huulen heittoa\" juhlitaan.'),(133192881,13386270,'Lipponen hämmästeli myös presidentti Sauli Niinistön osuutta Suomen politiikassa.'),(133192882,13386270,'- Miksi presidentti ei tue hallitusta, jolla on vaikeampi tilanne kuin omalla hallituksellani aikoinaan?'),(133192883,13386270,'Lähde: Yle Uutiset'),(133192884,13386271,'Iltalehti kertoi pääsiäisenä, kuinka keskusrikospoliisin taannoinen operaatio November osoittautui täydelliseksi flopiksi.'),(133192885,13386271,'IL:n haltuunsa saama salainen pakkokeinomateriaali osoitti, että poliisi ei vaihtanut löytämäänsä usean kilon amfetamiinierää vaarattomaan aineeseen, vaan jätti kätkön koskemattomaksi.'),(133192886,13386271,'Kätkön viereen viritettiin kuitenkin kamerat ja hälyttimet. Kun kätkö hälytti ja poliisit ehtivät paikalle, \"ketunkolo\" oli jo tyhjennetty. Kuvissa näkyi, kuinka kaksi tunnettua huumerikollista juoksi metsästä autolleen. Ainakin toisella oli nyytit selvästi käsissään.'),(133192887,13386271,'Moka kirjattiin'),(133192888,13386271,'Iltalehden saamat uudet dokumentit koskevat Novemberin tapahtumapäiväkirjaa. Sen teksti on tiivistä ja tylyä luettavaa:'),(133192889,13386271,'23.8.2005 klo 21:00 Filmille ketunpesän tyhjennys. Tunnistettu Jorkka ja Pekka.'),(133192890,13386271,'24.8. klo 14:32 Meikäläinen ilmoitti, että ketunpesältä on havainto eilen illalta kahdesta autosta. Toinen Mazda (rek.nro) ja punainen Mondeo (rek.nro). Jälkimmäisestä kaksi metsään n. klo 21.00. Viipyivät n. 15 min. ensin toinen autolla ja hieman jäljessä juosten toinen, jolla käsissään kumihanskat ja molemmissa käsissä \"munamaiset\" paketit. Tarkistuksessa todettu, että Mondeo on RG:n (Rogues Gallery) Pekan käytössä. (Kummankin nimet sivumerkinnässä).'),(133192891,13386271,'Vielä samana päivänä KRP joutui ilmoittamaan Oulun yksikölleen mokansa:'),(133192892,13386271,'24.8. klo 14:40 Teikäläiselle (KRP:n tutkija) Ouluun ilmoitettu: \"RG saanut eilen todennäköisesti 2 kg tavaraa päällensä\".'),(133192893,13386271,'Salainen seuranta ketunpesällä kuitenkin jatkui. Vaikka tunnettuja huumerikollisia tuli ja meni, ketään ei otettu kiinni.'),(133192894,13386271,'Pillerit kateisiin'),(133192895,13386271,'Päiväkirja osoittaa, että Vantaan Hämeenkylän maastossa sijainnut \"ketunkolo\" ei ollut ainoa operaatio Novemberissa seurattu kätkö. Eikä sen amfetamiini suinkaan ainoa rikollisille päätynyt huume.'),(133192896,13386271,'Seuraavana keväänä Myyrmäestä löytyi maastokätkö, jossa oli runsaasti ekstaasi-tabletteja. Päiväkirja kertoo:'),(133192897,13386271,'10.4.20