ter Abdullah Abdullah and former World Bank executive Ashraf Ghani, many wonder whether their next leader will match Mr. Karzai\'s sartorial heights.'),(133192934,13386275,'\"President Karzai is famous for being the most stylish leader in the world,\" said Hamid Rahimi, a Kabul-based tailor. \"In all seriousness, nobody can be like him. And that\'s obvious to the whole world.\"'),(133192935,13386275,'Mr. Rahimi took so much pride in Mr. Karzai\'s status as a global fashion icon that he spent years looking for funding to stitch together the world\'s largest pirhan-tumban—a traditional loose pants-and-tunic combination—in the president\'s honor. That plan was eventually shelved.'),(133192936,13386275,'The two presidential contenders—Mr. Abdullah and Mr. Ghani—have already put up something of a fashion show on the campaign trail. In stage appearances, they have worn capes and turbans in dozens of styles and colors.'),(133192937,13386275,'The two men, who are heading for the election\'s runoff in June, have carefully selected their wardrobes depending on the location of their speeches. They wore colorful chapan overcoats in the north, striped, long-tailed turbans in the east, and solid bankers\' suits in Kabul.'),(133192938,13386275,'\"They are trying to out-native each other. Like, \'I\'m more Afghan than you,\'\" says anthropologist Morwari Zafar, a doctoral candidate at the University of Oxford who has done research on image making among Afghans. '),(133192939,13386275,'Some say sartorial moves don\'t work for them. \"Clothes are not going to influence how we think,\" says Ahmad Walid Sediqqi, a 17-year-old agriculture student, who on a recent morning was wearing double-shaded sunglasses, skinny jeans and a leather satchel. \"Our generation is not illiterate. Neither candidate can fool us.\"'),(133192940,13386275,'In a televised debate earlier this year, Mr. Ghani, a former World Bank executive who is just as at home in Washington as he is in Kabul, appeared in a white pirhan-tumban, the pants-and-tunic combination, accessorized with a tsadar, a thick shawl, and prayer beads.'),(133192941,13386275,'Mr. Abdullah, a former mujahedeen commander, chose to wear a three-piece suit accented with a powder-blue tie and pocket square. '),(133192942,13386275,'The front-runner who won 44.9% of the ballots cast in April\'s first round election, Mr. Abdullah says he prides himself on his ability to dress well—and jokes that he introduced Mr. Karzai to his tailor.'),(133192943,13386275,'\"I have never been in a sartorial race with anybody in my life and this has not been my priority,\" Mr. Abdullah said in an interview. \"But at the same time I will credit myself with being able to match one or two things when I pay some attention.\"'),(133192944,13386275,'Over dinner one recent evening, Mr. Abdullah revealed the origin of the hand-embroidered black pirhan tumban he was wearing: a gift from supporters in the southern city of Kandahar. The embroidery took three months of work, he said. '),(133192945,13386275,'\"They know my taste,\" said Mr. Abdullah, wearing an Indian shawl carefully folded over his left shoulder and black velvet loafers with red soles.'),(133192946,13386275,'Mr. Ghani, for his part, said that his shifting wardrobe has a deeper political meaning in Afghanistan\'s ethnic and tribal mosaic.'),(133192947,13386275,'\"What\'s important to us is an acknowledgment. We are a nation that draws its strength from its diversity,\" said Mr. Ghani, who garnered 31.5% of the vote in April\'s first round. \"Part of my clothes change and part of them remain constant.\"'),(133192948,13386275,'In paying a tribute to local accouterments, both candidates have taken a cue from Mr. Karzai, whose outfit became a powerful symbol of national unity in the post-Taliban era.'),(133192949,13386275,'Mr. Karzai rarely, if ever, strays from his signature look. An ethnic Pashtun from the south, he wears green-and-purple silk chapans, overcoats that are traditionally worn by ethnic Uzbeks from the country\'s north.'),(133192950,13386275,'His preferred headgear, the fur karakul cap, is most popular among older men in Kabul and in the north. When Mr. Karzai first came to power, the hat helped draw the fashion spotlight on Afghanistan despite its unpleasant origin: It is typically made from the fur of fetal lambs.'),(133192951,13386275,'In Kabul, Mr. Karzai\'s characteristic pirhan tunic has become so popular that there is a style named after him. \"Our customers always ask for a Karzai Collar,\" says Mr. Rahimi, the tailor.'),(133192952,13386275,'Another tailor, Faizuddin Amiri, says neither candidate can hope to rival Mr. Karzai\'s wardrobe. \"They can\'t be as good as President Karzai,\" he says. \"Why? Because wherever he went he stuck to his own style.\" '),(133192953,13386275,'How the Karzai outfit came together is one of the founding myths of post-9/11 Afghanistan: Some officials say Mr. Karzai came up with it by himself, while others say he was gifted the chapan by the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance, and the karakul cap by a tribal elder.'),(133192954,13386275,'Mr. Karzai didn\'t respond to requests for comment.'),(133192955,13386275,'Either way, Mr. Karzai\'s attire delivered a message.'),(133192956,13386275,'\"Some people thought that was a sartorial decision. But he was very very sincere about this: this was symbolic,\" says Thomas Gouttierre, a veteran Afghanistan expert at the University of Nebraska who has known Mr. Karzai for decades. \"His statement was: I dress like this intentionally, I want everybody in Afghanistan to know I want to be a president of the whole country.\"'),(133192957,13386275,'Thus far, neither Mr. Abdullah nor Mr. Ghani has appeared in public with a karakul hat, the accessory most closely associated with Mr. Karzai.'),(133192958,13386275,'Mr. Abdullah said he isn\'t going to. Ever. \"This is a choice,\" he said. If elected, he promised a dramatic makeover of the presidential uniform. \"Cap and cape no,\" he said. \"It won\'t be monotonous.\"'),(133192959,13386275,'—Ehsanullah Amiri contributed to this article.'),(133192960,13386275,' Write to Margherita Stancati at margherita.stancati@wsj.com and Nathan Hodge at nathan.hodge@wsj.com '),(133192961,13386276,'Hänen mukaansa niemimaan kohtalo on jäänyt keskusteluissa toiseksi, kun kaikki huomio on kiinnittynyt Itä-Ukrainan tilanteeseen.'),(133192962,13386276,'- Me haluamme olla osa Ukrainaa, me tuomitsemme tämän valtauksen, Dzhemilev sanoi Wienissä.'),(133192963,13386276,'Reilu kymmenesosa Krimin asukkaista on tataareja. Dzhemilevin mukaan Ukrainan keskushallintoa kannattavia tataareja on pakotettu jättämään kotinsa.'),(133192964,13386276,'Krimin uudet vallanpitäjät estivät myös Dzhemilevin pääsyn takaisin niemimaalle, mutta hän aikoo jatkaa yrittämistä.'),(133192965,13386276,'- Emme aio jättää miehittäjiä nauttimaan rauhasta, hän lupasi.'),(133192966,13386277,'Kaliforniasta kotoisin oleva Erika \"Amazon Eve\" Ervin on tehnyt näyttävästä vartalostaan itselleen elinkeinon.'),(133192967,13386277,'35-vuotias nainen herättää huomiota minne meneekin, sillä hänellä on pituutta peräti 208 senttiä. Ennen menestystään mallina, näyttelijänä ja tv-juontajana Eve häpesi pituuttaan. Hän yritti piiloutua maailmalta ja työskenteli lakifirmassa.'),(133192968,13386277,'Eve hyväksyi pituutensa vasta innostuttuaan kuntosaliharjoittelusta ja opiskeltuaan personal traineriksi. Hän pääsi kiertämään maailmaa isokokoisten naisten Amazons-ryhmän kanssa. Australiassa Evestä tehtiin lehtijuttu ja video, jotka esittelivät hänet miljoonille katsojille.'),(133192969,13386277,'Eve sai runsaasti kansainvälistä huomiota ja nousi nopeasti menestyväksi malliksi. Vuonna 2011 Guinnesin ennätysten kirja listasi Amazon Even maailman pisimmäksi ammattimalliksi.'),(133192970,13386277,'Huhtikuussa amatsonimalli kuitenkin teki suuren paljastuksen. Aftonbladet-lehti kertoo, kuinka Erika Ervin paljasti ruotsalaisessa Renées Rubriker -tv-show\'ssa