lar taste in things worth guarding. You edge between tables loaded with obsolete games, arcane toys, wooden blocks made to introduce Jazz Age children to letters and numbers, small bronze sculptures of animals, toy furniture, and unidentifiable objects with apparently incomprehensible functions. You step around collapsing piles of Victorian engravings, penmanship exercises of astonishing elegance, botanical and architectural prints, century-old homework pages, and indescribable wooden fragments. Everything has an impressive patina of age and use. The paint on the blocks is rubbed away, the sharp edges of their relief letters blunted. '),(133193185,13386292,'Soon, you realize that the shelves lining the walls are similarly filled, but not, as you first assumed, with more of Mr. Boghosian\'s lovingly amassed raw material; rather, they are crowded with finished collages and constructions assembled from the infinite oddments on the floor and tables. Some are improvisations on mythological themes, others riffs on celebrated works of art or comments on historical events. Some, at the opposite end of the spectrum, embody elevated puns. A small sculpture of a dog occupies a plinth with an elevated sphere: \"Dog barking at the moon!\" One of many small alligator heads, mouth agape, has the bowl of a flat, padded representation of a familiar looking pipe shoved between its teeth: \"Cela n\'est pas un pipe—an homage to Magritte,\" Mr. Boghosian says.'),(133193186,13386292,'There\'s nothing quite like seeing the studio. But through May 25 visitors to the Toledo Museum of Art can sample the unique poetry of Mr. Boghosian\'s art through a thoughtful survey, selected by the Toledo Museum\'s associate director and curator, Amy Gilman, in collaboration with the artist. The show explores some of Mr. Boghosian\'s major preoccupations in works ranging from subtle two-dimensional collages to three-dimensional, sculpturelike constructions. His fascination with myth, for example, is revealed through a group of collages that incorporate images of snakes, swans and skulls, all scavenged from old prints, sometimes combined with exquisite drawing. Leda and the Swan, Adam and Eve, even Laocöon and other well-known tales are suggested obliquely by ambiguous images such as \"Serpent + Swan\" (2011); one of this group, which includes an elegant Ingres-esque drawn profile, seems to take on the whole history of Neo-Classicism. '),(133193187,13386292,'At the heart of Mr. Boghosian\'s artful combinations is Surrealism\'s belief that things gain in meaning when they are taken out of context and placed in unexpected relationships—as they often are in dreams; Max Ernst\'s \"appropriations\" of lurid engravings are precedents, as are the work of the Italian Metaphysical painters, such as Giorgio de Chirico, who, like Mr. Boghosian, sometimes incorporated the wooden mannequins once used by artists into their efforts, as surrogate figures. But Mr. Boghosian\'s meticulously crafted, evocative images are wholly his own. He seamlessly joins things of different scales and different eras so that the parts are completely subsumed by the new whole, which seems independent of precedent. Unexpected ambiguous meanings entirely replace the original identities of the various elements, yet the visible evidence of their previous lives—rubs, tears, the aura of age—enriches Mr. Boghosian\'s works. The physical, material character of each of his diverse components contributes significantly to mood and meaning. Discarded and forgotten things are given new life.'),(133193188,13386292,'The element of time is added by a series of \"shelf sculptures,\" in which three-dimensional objects are presented for our scrutiny in series or unpredictable combinations. Their placement seems provisional, temporary; their balance seems precarious. The configuration before us could be changed or might even change spontaneously, because of the effects of gravity. A related sculptural work, \"The Realm of the Oracle\" (1989), confronts us with a half-length metal female mannequin engaged in an inexplicable ritual, triggering associations with everything from 18th-century automatons to rowdy carnival games. '),(133193189,13386292,'Other works evoke artists such as Thomas Eakins (black discs and a white ball, against a dark ground, suggesting his shadowy light) and De Chirico (jigsaw puzzle pieces with fragments of his signature train and arcade motifs). Mr. Boghosian\'s sense of connection to the art of the past and recent past, manifest in these assemblages, is subtly underlined by the inclusion, at key points in the show, of apposite works from the Toledo Museum\'s collections. A snake armband from ancient Greece and a ravishing Giorgio Morandi still life resonate with Mr. Boghosian\'s mythological themes and shelf sculptures; a moonlit Joseph Stella landscape with a tall tree is paired with a moody Boghosian of a miniature lamppost, creating an interesting conversation between the common vertical elements and somber lighting of both works. (Further interesting conversations took place in another gallery, during most of the run of the exhibition. Mr. Boghosian provided a lavish selection of his own materials for children to assemble their own versions of his work, arranging things on shelves and photographing the results.) '),(133193190,13386292,'Mr. Boghosian is a kind of cult figure, not a household name, but a highly regarded artist ardently treasured by those who have discovered his uncanny, provocative work. The Toledo show not only explains the enthusiasm of his devoted fans—I count myself among them—but undoubtedly will also create new ones.'),(133193191,13386292,' Ms. Wilkin is an art critic and independent curator.  '),(133193192,13386293,'Toivo pilkahti vuosia ahdingossa eläneessä telakkateollisuudessa, kun tuli ilmi valtion ja maineikkaan saksalaisen telakkayhtiön ostotarjouksesta korealaiselle STX-konsernille Turun telakasta.'),(133193193,13386293,'Mutt