, perusteli syyttäjä T.J. Donovan päätöstä jättää syyte nostamatta.'),(133193515,13386317,'Kuollut mies oli uhkaillut vaimoaan ja lapsiaan aseella ensimmäisen kerran jo yli vuotta aiemmin. Tapausta ei kuitenkaan tuolloin ilmoitettu virkavallalle, syyttäjä sanoi.'),(133193516,13386317,'Lähde: AP'),(133193517,13386318,'There is little consensus in the often-contentious world of jazz, but most fans and critics agree that Sonny Rollins is the greatest tenor saxophonist alive. And, at age 83, Mr. Rollins is still in peak form. For decades, attendance at his concerts has taken on the solemnity of a pilgrimage. But for many of those years, none of his recordings were a match for the classics like \"Saxophone Colossus\" (Prestige, 1956), \"Freedom Suite\" (Riverside, 1958) and \"East Broadway Rundown\" (Impulse!, 1966) that established his reputation. The newer recordings lacked the intense probing on up-tempo numbers and the poignancy on ballads. Six years ago Mr. Rollins found the right approach to recordings—releasing compilations of his live work. Now his albums prompt a similar hushed level of anticipation as his performances.'),(133193518,13386318,'On Tuesday, Mr. Rollins released \"Road Shows Vol. 3\" (Doxy/Sony Music Masterworks), and it is the equal of its heralded predecessors \"Road Shows Vol. 1\" (Doxy/EmArcy 2008) and \"Road Shows Vol. 2\" (Doxy/EmArcy 2011). Each volume has a distinctive identity. Volume 1 spans 27 years of Mr. Rollins\'s career; it includes the tracks of his remarkable 2007 concert commemorating the 50th anniversary of his first Carnegie Hall appearance. Volume 2 comprises material from 2010, the year of Mr. Rollins\'s 80th birthday, including the superb Beacon Theater performance where he was joined by guitarist Jim Hall, drummer Roy Haynes, trumpeter Roy Hargrove, bassist Christian McBride and—in a complete surprise to the audience—saxophonist Ornette Coleman. The new recording features material since the turn of the century, and its best parts reveal the strengths of Mr. Rollins\'s working band rather than guest stars joining the performance.'),(133193519,13386318,'Mr. Rollins combines a commanding tone with a ferocious, intense appetite for melodic exploration in his solos, and each volume is highlighted by an extended presentation of this tendency. Unlike \"Blossom\" from the first \"Road Show\" or \"Sonnymoon for Two\" on the second, the highlight of the third, \"Someday I\'ll Find You,\" is a ballad. It also reveals Mr. Rollins\'s newfound willingness to reconsider his previous work. The song was written as a ballad in 1930 by Noël Coward for his play \"Private Lives,\" but when Mr. Rollins first recorded it in 1958 he performed it up-tempo. Here, it is returned to its original pace. Following a terse, pungent solo by guitarist Bobby Broom, Mr. Rollins begins a lengthy exploration of the tune\'s melody—working chorus after chorus, playing one affecting passage after another, building toward a remarkable finale. Such are the moments that have made Rollins concerts so esteemed. Fans can often cite particular shows where the saxophonist played a tune, perhaps an original or a staple of the American songbook, with extraordinary depth and intensity. '),(133193520,13386318,'Other highlights of Volume 3 include the rugged but catchy \"Patanjali,\" named for the compiler of the yoga sutras. (Mr. Rollins\'s interest in yoga predates the current fad by decades.) \"Solo Sonny\" captures a unique trait of Mr. Rollins\'s playing. Performing unaccompanied, he seems to quote a dizzying series of tunes ranging from movie themes to Tin Pan Alley numbers to children\'s songs. It\'s the sort of madcap sequencing and pacing that usually requires the latest technology, but Mr. Rollins needs only a horn and a stage.'),(133193521,13386318,'The most consistent criticism of Mr. Rollins\'s concerts is that he cedes too much solo space to his bandmates, and that tendency mars the recording\'s longest track, \"Why Was I Born,\" which quickly turns into an exchange between the saxophonist and drummer Steve Jordan. The percussionist\'s part of the dialogue grows repetitive after a few minutes, though Mr. Rollins storms on, playing one inventive phrase after another.'),(133193522,13386318,'Mr. Rollins is notoriously self-critical; in 1959, after releasing several widely hailed recordings, many of which are now regarded as classics, he retired from the music business until 1962; he felt he needed to work on his sound, and he was occasionally heard practicing his horn on the Williamsburg Bridge. He is also dedicated to performing. In 1986, during a concert in upstate New York, he jumped off of a 6-foot-high stage and broke his heel, yet he continued to play. Mr. Rollins and his wife, Lucille, who died in 2004, lived in Tribeca, not far from the World Trade Center, and had to be evacuated the day after the 2001 attacks, yet he insisted on making his performance in Boston three days later. That appearance was documented on \"Without a Song: The 9/11 Concert\" (Milestone, 2005).'),(133193523,13386318,'Perhaps it is no surprise that Mr. Rollins is still going strong just a few months shy of his 84th birthday. During an interview in the mid-\'80s, he told me that \"the glory isn\'t in grasping the ring; the glory is in reaching for it.\" '),(133193524,13386318,'At the time, I thought it was a veteran musician giving a young journalist a nifty quote. But evidently it really is Mr. Rollins\'s modus operandi.'),(133193525,13386318,' Mr. Johnson writes about jazz for the Journal. '),(133193526,13386319,'Niinistön mukaan Ukrainan kriisi on synnyttänyt vihan kierteen maassa, mutta hän suhtautui toiveikkaasti Venäjän presidentti Vladimir Putinin eiliseen puheeseen.'),(133193527,13386319,'Niinistö on viimeksi ollut puhelinyhteydessä Putiniin helmikuussa Ukrainan kriisin tiimoilta. Iltalehden tiedustellessa Niinistöltä, miksei hän ole ollut tämän jälkeen yhteydessä kollegaansa, Niinistö totesi tympääntyneenä:'),(133193528,13386319,'-Luulen, että olen ollut silläkin puhelulla enemmän yhteydessä kuin Euroopan Unionin valtioiden päämiehet keskimäärin. Jos sitä joku ihmettelee, niin kertoisin sitten, että mistä hänen kanssaan nyt olisi pitänyt erityisesti puhua.'),(133193529,13386319,'Niinistö painotti, että presidentin kansliasta pidetään jatkuvasti yhteyttä Venäjälle ja jos tarvetta tämän haarukoinnin pohjalta ilmenee, hän on yhteydessä Putiniin.'),(133193530,13386319,'Presidentin suunnitelmissa onkin olla Putiniin yhteydessä lähiaikoina.'),(133193531,13386319,'-Meille tulee Viron presidentti vierailulle ja Venäjälläkin taitaa olla voitonpäivä. Niiden jälkeen mahdollisesti, Niinistö kertoi.'),(133193532,13386320,'Can music heal? There\'s been a great deal of study by neuroscientists on the different ways music acts upon the brain, affecting our behavior, memory and the like. But there is also growing scientific evidence attesting to its curative powers. '),(133193533,13386320,'Many ancient cultures used sound and music for healing. Pythagoras called it \"music medicine.\" In the Middle Ages, the study of music became a mandatory part of a physician\'s education. '),(133193534,13386320,'In this country, music therapy began to develop as a profession during World War I, and in World War II music was incorporated into the Army\'s Reconditioning Program under direct supervision of medical personnel, the first official recognition of music as a therapeutic aid by the military. And in the 1930s researchers discovered that sounds made by the ancients\' drums, rattles and didgeridoos—so-called ultrasound—had huge diagnostic and healing properties. Today there are more than 5,000 certified music therapists in the U.S., and more than 70 colleges and universities offer music-therapy programs treating everything from posttraumatic stress disorder to Parkinson\'s disease, Alzheimer\'s and pain.'),(133193535,13386320,'In his book \"Awakenings,\" the British-American neurologist Oliver Sacks writes of patients who went from being catatonic to fully functional when music was added to their environment.'),(133193536,13386320,'In our own time there have been many stories about the healing power of music. One of the most famous is William Styron\'s. He writes of the moment music saved him from suicide in \"Darkness Visible: A Memoir of Madness.\" While watching \"The Bostonians\" on television in the 1980s, he heard Brahms\'s Alto Rhapsody on the soundtrack. The music brought back \"all the joys the house had known. ... All this I realized was more than I could ever abandon. ... And just as powerfully I realized I could not commit this desecration on myself.\" '),(133193537,13386320,'After Gabrielle Giffords was shot in 2011, intensive singing therapy slowly brought back her ability to speak.'),(133193538,13386320,'I recently witnessed the healing effects of music first hand. As part of their \"National Initiative for Arts and Health in the Military,\" I was invited by Americans for the Arts to visit the Walter Reed National Military Medical Center and participate in \"Stages of Healing.\" This program, created by Dr. Micah Sickel, helps patients learn how to play a musical instrument and facilitates live performances whose aim, according to the hospital, is to \"enhance the healing process ... enrich the lives of patients, visitors and staff\" and help relieve the stress often associated with a hospital setting. '),(133193539,13386320,'I knew what I wanted to play for them—two Chopin waltzes and \"A Hero\'s Passing By\" (which I had written for a TV documentary on my wife\'s father, Gary Cooper, but performed here as a dedication to all the world\'s heroes). I then played two songs from a musical I had written about the Hunchback of Notre Dame. One was a love song and the other is titled \"Like Any Man,\" which I felt very much suited the occasion. The Hunchback sings that although he is so disabled, he is just like any man.'),(133193540,13386320,'The piano was placed in the middle of a beautiful, large, circular, blue, star-ringed carpet in a spacious open area. Furniture was arranged on one side so people could sit on couches and chairs quite close to the piano. On the other side, folding chairs were set up for an audience who, given their medical schedules, family visits, etc., were able to come go as needed. It felt like there was very intense listening going on and, for me, very emotional playing. There was a sense of activity everywhere—patients, staff, visitors, all getting on with their lives.'),(133193541,13386320,'After my performance, my wife and I talked with some of our brave young veterans suffering from a range of physical and psychological conditions. Many told me how much music had helped their recovery.'),(133193542,13386320,'Barry Bittman is a renowned neurologist and top researcher in the studies of sound, music and the brain. He is the president of the Yamaha Music and Wellness Institute, with which I am affiliated. I once asked him whether there was a difference in the effects of listening to versus playing music. \"Statistically significant benefits,\" he said, \"extended exclusively to the group creating music,\" which requires \"a high level of engagement on many levels.\" Dr. Bittman\'s research on creative musical expression, even for people convinced that they were not musical, also recently proved that playing any kind of instrument—no matter how well or badly—enhances the brain\'s ability to facilitate healing. '),(133193543,13386320,'This is confirmed in another program at Walter Reed called Musicorps, where, working with professional musicians, computer-based music workstations and actual instruments, patients learn, play, compose and record music. It is designed to help patients suffering from PTSD and traumatic brain injury. \"Learning, creating, and performing music involves so many aspects of brain function that it is believed to recruit uninjured parts of the brain to compensate for parts that have been injured, and help those parts that are injured recover,\" notes the hospital in its literature on the program. '),(133193544,13386320,'The memory of our visit to Walter Reed stayed with us long after we\'d returned home, and I wanted to be more involved. Then I learned about Music for All Seasons, which hosts performances at venues in New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Connecticut and California. Founded by husband and wife Brian Dallow and Rena Fruchter out of the belief that live music has \"a therapeutic, educational and healing influence on all who listen and participate,\" it is now in its 22nd season. Their newest initiative, Voices of Valor, brings groups of six to 10 veterans together with two musician facilitators to write their lyrics to a group song, set it to music and record it in a professional studio. The CD is then presented to the veterans\' friends and family. '),(133193545,13386320,'I visited a transitional housing facility in Glen Gardner, N.J., called Veteran\'s Haven North, where men who had served in various wars were in the middle of an eight-week program. I asked to hear their stories and they asked me if I would share mine. (Though they were not the result of combat, I have had serious injuries to my hands and disabilities to overcome in the course of my 75-year career as a concert pianist.) As we shared our experiences and feelings, I played the same music as I had at Walter Reed.'),(133193546,13386320,'They then sang me a powerful song they were working on. Here are some of the lyrics:'),(133193547,13386320,' On the outside I\'m fine '),(133193548,13386320,' On the inside are scars '),(133193549,13386320,' We\'re fighting for a freedom '),(133193550,13386320,' But the freedom\'s not ours '),(133193551,13386320,' Just because I\'m not on the battlefield '),(133193552,13386320,' Doesn\'t mean I\'m not at war '),(133193553,13386320,' May not be who I used to be '),(133193554,13386320,' But I\'m so much more '),(133193555,13386320,'Several weeks later I was elated to learn that one of the men was so inspired that he planned to take a course in music at Rutgers University. I only wished they knew how much they inspired me.'),(133193556,13386320,' Mr. Janis is a world-renowned concert pianist particularly known for his interpretations of Chopin, and the author of \"Chopin and Beyond: My Extraordinary Life in Music and the Paranormal,\" an autobiography. '),(133193557,13386321,'Suomen sosialidemokraattisen puolueen puoluekokous Seinäjoella alkaa puolilta päivin Seinäjoen Areenassa äärimmäisen jännittävissä tunnelmissa.'),(133193558,13386321,'Kokouksen alla on edustajia käännytetty ja juntattu olan takaa kahden puheenjohtajaehdokkaan taakse. Istuvan puheenjohtajan Jutta Urpilaisen haastajalla, Ammattiliitto Pron puheenjohtaja Antti Rinteellä on puoluekokouksessa niukka enemmistö.'),(133193559,13386321,'Iltalehden Rinteen esikunnasta keskiviikkona saaman tiedon mukaan Rinnettä kannattaa 253 kokousedustajaa kaikkiaan 500:sta. Tänään on kuulemma tullut vielä muutama lisää.'),(133193560,13386321,'Jos tuo tieto pitää kutinsa vielä perjantain vaalissa, se merkitsee puheenjohtajan vaihtumista SDP:ssä. Se merkitsisi myös valtiovarainministerin ja pääministerin sijaisen vaihtumista.'),(133193561,13386321,'Paljon voi kuitenkin vielä tapahtua perjantain vastaisen yön junttauksissa, joten kovin suurista summista ei vetoa äänestyksen tuloksesta vielä kannata lyödä.'),(133193562,13386321,'Iltalehden politiikan toimittaja Tommi Parkkonen tviittaa puoluekokouksesta. Parkkosen tviitit alla.'),(133193563,13386322,'15-16 prosentin tuntumassa itsepintaisesti kuukaudesta toiseen laahaavat kannatuslukemat pakottava tekemään jotain radikaalia. Mutta mitä, kas siinä kysymys.'),(133193564,13386322,'Ay-johtaja Antti Rinteen nostaminen puheenjohtajaksi hirvittää monia, mutta Ruotsissakin demareiden korpivaellus näyttää päättyneen ay-pomon johdolla. SDP kaipaa nykyistä selkeämpää aatteellista profiilia, mutta eri asia on, syntyisikö Rinteen johdolla oikea, tulevaisuuteen viittaava julkisuuskuva ja linja.'),(133193565,13386322,'Olipa puoluekokouksen voimasuhde puheenjohtajan valinnassa lopulta niin tai näin, se on selvää, että joka toinen näkee Jutta Urpilaisen lasin olevan puoliksi tyhjä, toiset puoliksi täysi. Samaa voi sanoa Rinteestä. Vaarana on, että väki jakautuu kahteen leiriin ja hävinnyt puoli passivoituu.'),(133193566,13386322,'Jutta Urpilaisesta ei välttämättä haluttaisi luopua juuri kun hän on valtiovarainministerinä saanut uskottavuutta. Pääministeri Jyrki Kataisen (kok) lähtiessä kesken kauden hallituksen johdosta, olisi kansakunnan kannalta riskaabelia vaihtaa myös hänen sijaisensa näinä levottomina aikoina?'),(133193567,13386322,'Mutta toisaalta Urpilainen on saanut tarpeeksi aikaa - kuusi vuotta - näyttää kykynsä puoluejohtajana. Vaalitulokset ovat olleet murheellisia. Puolue näyttää jääneen huonolle hoidolle. Olisiko \"puolueen toimitusjohtaja\", puoluesihteeri Reijo Paananen pantava tästä vastuuseen ja vaihtoon?'),(133193568,13386323,'With his supple, backwoods baritone and twanging guitar,                                                                        Sturgill Simpson                                                                was hailed as a savior of traditional country music when his debut album, \"High Top Mountain,\" clicked with critics last year. '),(133193569,13386323,'Now Mr. Simpson is turning tradition on its ear with an ambitious follow-up, \"Metamodern Sounds in Country Music,\" due May 13. The album salts old-school country, bluegrass and gospel sounds with hints of psychedelia and even electronica—although fans of his authentic-country cred aren\'t likely to be disappointed. '),(133193570,13386323,'\"We rolled back and forth between these very traditional raw sounds and \'computerized\' music that we made without computers,\" he says in a rich Kentucky drawl. \"The whole album was recorded just me and my band live-to-tape. We manipulated those recordings through analog machinery using various outdated techniques—to make modern music.'),(133193571,13386323,'\"The title is very much a nod to                                                                        Ray Charles,                                                               \" adds Mr. Simpson, an admirer of the soul great\'s seminal \"Modern Sounds in Country and Western Music,\" from 1962. \"But also I\'m a gigantic smartass. There\'s a lot going on in country music, with indie-label hipsters and underground bloggers arguing their interpretations of what country is, and pop country stars defending themselves. That deserves to be poked fun at.'),(133193572,13386323,'As for his lyrics, they brim with references to psychoactive drugs and his interest in metaphysics, Tibetan Buddhism, Hindu mythology, cosmology and all manner of esoterica seldom treated by Nashville tunesmiths.'),(133193573,13386323,'\"I\'m always reading this crazy cosmology and theoretical philosophy and metaphysical stuff and listening to [audio] lectures by                                                                        Terrence McKenna.                                                                He\'s a linguist guy who has this theory that the only reason mankind evolved was because there were [psilocybin] mushrooms scattered over the African plains and we got out of that earlier brutish state because we were all walking around blasted out of our minds on mushrooms.'),(133193574,13386323,'\"It\'s an interesting idea,\" Mr. Simpson muses; \"doesn\'t mean it\'s true.\"'),(133193575,13386323,'Thanks to two people closest to him, Mr. Simpson is well aware that his new songs strike some as loopy. \"My wife thinks I\'m crazy. We have a baby due in June and she said \'If you\'re going to keep driving me insane talking about this stuff, why don\'t you just write songs about it and get it out of your system.\' I thought, \'That\'s a great idea.\"'),(133193576,13386323,'Some were more skeptical. Mr. Simpson\'s grandfather is heard at the beginning of the album introducing \"Metamodern Sounds in Country Music\" in a disembodied voice that sounds like a Grand Ole Opry broadcast from outer space. \"He\'s from the darkest holler in all of eastern Kentucky,\" says Mr. Simpson, who recorded him on a cellphone. \"He\'s 82; he was born in a coal camp. I said \'Papaw, I want you to MC this record.\' It took about 18 tries. He was like, \'Meta? Modern? What the hell are you doin\'?\'\"'),(133193577,13386323,'Now 35, Mr. Simpson, the son of a coal miner\'s daughter and an undercover narcotics policeman, grew up around Jackson, Ky. \"It\'s in Appalachia,\" he says. \"It was a boomin\' little coal town in the \'70s and \'80s. Strip mining and deep mining was the only real industry. Once that dried up, Wal-Mart, OxyContin and heroin moved in. That was pretty much all she wrote.\"'),(133193578,13386323,'But Mr. Simpson\'s boyhood was awash in the sounds of old-time country and bluegrass. \"I always played music,\" he says. \"Both my grandfathers and my mother\'s brother were musicians. Back home, playing music is never anything you imagine you can do for a living. It\'s what you do after work.\"'),(133193579,13386323,'After high school—\"I barely got through,\" he says; \"I was bored, unfocused and kind of rebellious\"—he joined the Navy. \"You get on the boat, you get off the boat and you binge drink. That was it for almost three years. I didn\'t pick up a guitar the entire time I was in.\"'),(133193580,13386323,'After his discharge, he says, \"I went buck wild.\" Drifting and drinking, he eventually returned to Kentucky where he began to play in public for the first time, performing at open-mic nights in a bar and joining Sunday Valley, a popular Lexington band that played what he calls \"amped-up punk-rock bluegrass.\"'),(133193581,13386323,'In 2005 he took a half-hearted shot at a solo career. \"I drove down to Nashville at a time when pop-country was saturating; I couldn\'t find anybody who wanted to play with me. I spent that year in the bottom of a bottle.\"'),(133193582,13386323,'He climbed out with the help of a friend who got him a job in a Utah railroad freight-shipping yard. \"I got sober and threw myself into working 70, 80 hours a week,\" he says. \"Trains would pull in and we\'d tear \'em apart and move \'em around and build new trains. It was like playin\' with a giant train set. I loved the job but I screwed up and took a management position and it slowly changed into \'I hate this job.\'\"'),(133193583,13386323,'Then living with his future wife, Mr. Simpson says she stealthily steered him toward his musical destiny. \"She bought a little 12-track digital recorder and started booking me gigs around town without telling me. I\'d think we\'re going out to dinner and we get there and she has the guitar out in the car; we go into this barbecue place and it turns out I gotta get up there and play five songs.\"'),(133193584,13386323,'She also burned CDs of his tunes and cold-called local radio stations that gave Mr. Simpson his first airplay. \"My wife was like, \'You\'re going to be 40 and wake up and realize you never actually tried.\' She was like, \'You don\'t suck at this.\' So we sold and gave away everything we could and moved to Nashville. That was four years ago.\"'),(133193585,13386323,'Tours and an album with Sunday Valley followed. In 2012, the group disbanded when Mr. Simpson left to make \"High Top Mountain.\" Once completed, he shopped it to record labels. \"Nobody touched it,\" Mr. Simpson says. \"it was too country for the hipsters and too country for the pop-country labels.\"'),(133193586,13386323,'In the end, he put it out himself through a distribution company. \"I\'m basically digging a giant hole of debt—but I\'m only in debt to me.\" '),(133193587,13386323,'He won the services of two country music studio legends, pedal-steel player                                                                        Robby Turner                                                                and                                                                        Hargus \"Pig\" Robbins,                                                                whom Mr. Simpson calls \"the greatest living country piano player on the entire planet.\" Also on board was producer                                                                        Dave Cobb,                                                                whose 2013 albums with                                                                        Jason Isbell                                                                and                                                                        Lindi Ortega                                                                joined Mr. Simpson\'s \"High Top Mountain\" on critics\' lists of the best country albums of the year.'),(133193588,13386323,'His debut\'s success brought offers from major labels to put out his follow-up, but Mr. Simpson demurred. \"I\'m so glad I did,\" he says, \"because as a direct result I got to make a country album about metaphysics and turtles and drugs.\" '),(133193589,13386324,'Urpilainen piti tärkeänä, että turvallisuuspoliittiset ratkaisut tehdään hyvän sään aikana.'),(133193590,13386324,'- Akuutin kansainvälisen kriisin vallitessa Nato-keskustelulla ei pidä tehdä puoluepolitiikkaa. Jännitteitä on pyrittävä purkamaan, ei lisäämään.'),(133193591,13386324,'Suomen turvallisuuspolitiikan pitkä linja on Urpilaisen mielestä myös ajankohtaisen kehityksen valossa kestävä ja perusteltu.'),(133193592,13386324,'Iltalehti seuraa puoluekokousta paikan päällä.'),(133193593,13386324,'Iltalehden politiikan toimittaja Tommi Parkkonen myös tviittaa puoluekokouksen tapahtumista. Parkkosen tviittejä voit seurata alla.'),(133193594,13386325,'Rinteen esikunta kertoi Iltalehdelle, että Antti Rinne johtaisi jo kisaa, häntä kannattaa ainakin 253 kokousedustajaa 500:sta.'),(133193595,13386325,'Tuoreimpien tietojen mukaan kannattajia olisi tullut vielä lisää.'),(133193596,13386325,'Jungner pitää Rinteen junttausta pelkkänä poliittisena psyykkauksena.'),(133193597,13386325,'- Tuo 253 edustajaa taitaa olla pikemminkin unelma kuin totta, Jungner sanoo.'),(133193598,13386325,'Jungnerin mielestä myös Rinteen kannattaisi keskittyä spekuloinnin sijaan oman linjansa kirkastamiseen.'),(133193599,13386325,'- Se olisi hyödyllisempää ja kiinnostavampaa.'),(133193600,13386325,'Urpilaisen vahvaksi tukijaksi profiloitunut Jungner vakuuttaa, että Jutan tiimissä on tekemisen meininki.'),(133193601,13386325,'- Jutta on hyvä ehdokas ja hänellä on hyvä linja.'),(133193602,13386325,'Urpilainen pitää illalla puheen, jossa hän kertoo poliittisen linjansa ja vasta perjantaiaamuna hän pitää ehdokaspuheensa.'),(133193603,13386326,'Venäläisten mediatietojen mukaan Venäjä on testannut torstaina ballistisia ohjuksia Pleseteskissä Arkangelin alueella, kertoo uutistoimisto AFP.'),(133193604,13386326,'Venäjän kerrotaan kokeilleen myös useita lyhyen matkan ohjuksia. Tiedotusvälineiden mukaan testiä valvoi itse presidentti Vladimir Putin.'),(133193605,13386326,'Puolustusministeri Sergei Shoigu puolestaan vakuutti Venäjän ydinaseiden olevan \"jatkuvassa taisteluvalmiudessa\", kertovat venäläiset uutistoimistot AFP:n mukaan.'),(133193606,13386326,'Putin, joka kertoi eilen käskeneensä venäläisjoukot pois Ukrainan rajan läheisyydestä, kuitenkin vakuutti, etteivät ennalta suunnitellut ohjuskokeet liity Ukrainan räjähdysherkkään tilanteeseen.'),(133193607,13386326,'Sen sijaan harjoituksen kerrotaan liittyneen natsi-Saksan kaatumisen perjantaiseen muistopäivään.'),(133193608,13386326,'Vierailleille Valko-Venäjän, Armenian, Tadzikistanin ja Kirgisian päämiehille isäntä hehkutti silti Venäjän asevoimien mahtia.'),(133193609,13386326,'- Olette saaneet todistaa maamme strategisten hyökkäys- ja puolustusvoimien suurta valmiutta ja yhtenäisyyttä, Putin lausui AFP:n mukaan.'),(133193610,13386326,'Lähde: AFP'),(133193611,13386327,'Spoiler alert: The actors who play singer-songwriters on the ABC television show \"Nashville\" can actually write songs. '),(133193612,13386327,'The cast of the country music soap concluded its first four-city tour with a sold-out show in New York on Tuesday night as \"Nashville\" nears the end of its second season. In addition to performing hits from the show, nearly every actor sang an original song.'),(133193613,13386327,'\"We\'ve got a honky-tonk right here in Times Square,\" announced Charles Esten (Deacon Claybourne), who acted as the genial MC for the evening and received the largest cheers from the predominantly female audience. \"New York City welcome to Nashville.\"'),(133193614,13386327,'It might not have been the Bluebird Cafe, the real-life Nashville venue featured on the show. But the 2,100-seat Best Buy theater fostered an informal atmosphere that felt more like an acoustic concert than celebrity-studded sing-a-thon.'),(133193615,13386327,'The cast—minus stars Connie Britton (Rayna Jaymes) and Hayden Panettiere (Juliette Barnes)—bounded on and offstage, mixing up the combinations of performers and playing backup guitar and drums for each other\'s songs.'),(133193616,13386327,'As opposed to \"Glee,\" which sold more than 70,000 tickets for its inaugural tour, \"I think we looked at it a little differently,\" said executive producer                                                                        Steven Buchanan.                                                                \"We wanted to build something that was both a showcase of the music from the show as well as to help draw attention to the incredible talents and musicianship of our cast.\"'),(133193617,13386327,'The actors didn\'t perform in character, but their original songs evoked their on-screen personas, from Mr. Esten\'s lovely, brooding meditation on encroaching darkness to Jonathan Jackson\'s (Avery Barkley) soulful love song which also appeared on the show and Clare Bowen\'s (Scarlett O\'Connor) pretty, wistful ode to recovering from the kind of heartbreak where you \"cried so hard you almost coughed up a lung,\" she told the crowd. Chris Carmack (Will Lexington) sang upbeat country rock, while Sam Palladio\'s (Gunnar Scott) song-story was a playful, poignant piece about a missed meeting between his grandfather and a lover in Nashville.'),(133193618,13386327,'More than 600,000 Nashville soundtracks have been sold, along with more than 3,000,000 individual track downloads, according to the record label Big Machine Label Group, which also represents artists such as Taylor Swift. '),(133193619,13386327,'The concert created a meta situation for the cast, many of whom played in bands and have toggled between acting and music throughout their careers: They are musicians acting as musicians who go on tour now going on tour. '),(133193620,13386327,'But performing is performing, they said. \"I don\'t know that you\'d be able to spot any real difference,\" Mr. Esten said about performing as Deacon versus himself. \"You\'re trying to be pretty truthful with the song, so I don\'t really put on a patina of a character—you\'re just trying to tell that story.\"'),(133193621,13386327,'Still, he\'s a little looser than his onscreen alter-ego. \"Deacon\'s a better guitar player so it all comes out in a wash,\" said Mr. Esten, 48 years old. '),(133193622,13386327,'Ms. Bowen said she started writing songs as a child, but was too shy to share them—perhaps the only similarity with her alter ego, she said.'),(133193623,13386327,'\"Scarlett is a totally different person than me,\" said Ms. Bowen, noting that her character doesn\'t have a manager to shield her like the more established stars. \"She walks around in a permanent state of fear. She\'s been taught to duck and cover.\"'),(133193624,13386327,'Ms. Bowen\'s emotional rendition of Scarlett\'s song \"Black Rose