ssa tytöt voivat käytännössä päätyä seksiorjiksi.'),(133193673,13386333,'- Minä menen naimisiin 12-vuotiaan naisen kanssa. Minä menen naimisiin 9-vuotiaan tytön kanssa, terroristijohtaja julisti.'),(133193674,13386333,'Olinpaikasta ei tietoa'),(133193675,13386333,'Terroristijohtajan rinnalla videolla seisoi kuusi naamioitunutta asemiestä ja taustalla näkyi kaksi avolava-autoa täynnä konepistooleja.'),(133193676,13386333,'Siepattujen tyttöjen olinpaikasta ei ole mitään tietoa.'),(133193677,13386333,'Nigerialaistyttöjen sieppaustapaus sai aluksi hyvin hitaasti kansainvälistä huomiota, mutta viime päivien kampanjointi sosiaalisessa mediassa on herättänyt myös kansainvälisen median ja valtiojohtajat. Yhdysvallat on luvannut Nigerialle apua tyttöjen saattamiseksi kotiin turvallisesti sekä Boko Haramin vastaiseen taisteluun.'),(133193678,13386333,'Boko Haram -terroristijärjestö tavoittelee väkivalloin jyrkän islamistisen valtion perustamista Pohjois-Nigeriaan. Järjestö on surmannut tuhansia ihmisiä viimeisen viiden vuoden aikana. Pelkästään tänä vuonna arviolta 1500 ihmistä on kuollut erilaisissa iskuissa. Väkivalta on keskittynyt maan koillisiin osavaltioihin, joissa on ollut hätätila voimassa jo viime vuoden toukokuusta lähtien.'),(133193679,13386334,'Vantaan seudun steinerkoulun oppilaat olivat koulupäivän sisätiloissa lukittujen ovien takana koulun läheiseen roskakatokseen jätetyn tunnistamattoman laukun vuoksi.'),(133193680,13386334,'Koulun oppilaiden löydös aiheutti iltapäivällä poliisioperaation. Koulun A-rakennus tyhjennettiin kokonaan oppilaista heti havainnon jälkeen.'),(133193681,13386334,'Poliisi on tutkinut koulun pihalta löytyneen laukun, eikä siitä löytynyt mitään rikokseen viittaavaa.'),(133193682,13386334,'Epäilyttävä laukku oli lehdenjakajan, kertoo koulun rehtori Liisa Hertell. Koulu toimii taas normaalisti.'),(133193683,13386335,'Kevan hallitus esittää Männistöä tehtävään yksimielisesti. Tällä hetkellä Männistö toimii YTHS:n toimitusjohtajana.'),(133193684,13386335,'Kevan valtuuskunta nimittää toimitusjohtajan 20. toukokuuta vastaamaan Kevan toiminnasta ja taloudesta.'),(133193685,13386335,'Toimitusjohtajan hakukriteereinä olivat muun muassa eläkealan ja työeläkejärjestelmän tuntemus. Lisäksi häneltä odotettiin vahvaa johtamiskokemusta.Toimitusjohtajan virkaa haki 48 henkilöä. Haku päättyi 4. huhtikuuta.'),(133193686,13386335,'Keva huolehtii kunta-alan, valtion, kirkon ja Kelan henkilöstön eläkeasioista, ja se hoitaa noin 1,3 miljoonan työntekijän työeläkepalveluita.'),(133193687,13386336,'As one of the world\'s most respected sleight-of-hand artists,                                                                        Ricky Jay                                                                has amassed a peer group of top magicians and cardsharps, and a stable of famous pals, from                                                                        Bob Dylan                                                                to                                                                        David Mamet.                                                                These days, however, he probably spends more time hanging out with book dealers, he says. \"I like them. They live by their wits and their knowledge.\" '),(133193688,13386336,'They also live off their earnings from insatiable collectors like him. At the New York Antiquarian Book Fair, held recently in the cavernous Park Avenue Armory, he wandered the booths with some new acquisitions in hand, two books about hand shadows, and greeted many dealers by first name.'),(133193689,13386336,'One seller asked his advice about a book whose blank pages reveal images when you blow on them, a specialty of Mr. Jay\'s. Another tried to tempt him with a book of illustrations of London street people, published in 1649 and bearing a price tag of $75,000. To one silver-haired gentleman who tipped him off to a set of miniature playing cards, Mr. Jay said, \"Thanks, kid.\" '),(133193690,13386336,'He incorporates the arcane history he studies into the patter of his one-man shows, several of which have been directed by Mr. Mamet. He has unearthed bizarre characters from the past—automatons, ceiling walkers, Lilliputians, master pickpockets—and used them to anchor his lectures and books, some of which are collectors\' items in their own right. These real-life characters no doubt informed the fictional characters he has played in TV shows and movies such as \"Deadwood\" and \"Boogie Nights.\" '),(133193691,13386336,'Mr. Jay is preparing to share his expertise, especially in magic, at an event that he\'s calling the Congress of Wonders. On July 11-14, in the upstate New York town of Rhinebeck, he\'ll reveal \"the truth about dishonesty,\" or so the schedule promises. Organized by a promoter who books fantasy music camps with rock stars, the symposium also features a handful of speakers picked by Mr. Jay. They include Jules Fisher, a Tony-winning lighting designer who will discuss the craft\'s often overlooked role in magic, and                                                                        Michael Weber,                                                                Mr. Jay\'s partner in a business called Deceptive Practices, which advises Hollywood productions on how to create illusions with props.'),(133193692,13386336,'For Mr. Jay, the event is a first in that it will involve an unusual amount of mingling with nonmagicians, opening him up to the inevitable \"How\'d you do that?\" Still, he has made it an indirect mission in his career to help people learn the difference between \"good magic and bad magic.\" His goal, in other words: showing the uninitiated how to discern when a performer is grounded in tradition and endless practice. \"Magic is one of those arts where if you\'re fooled, by nature you think that the person who fooled you must have been good,\" he said.'),(133193693,13386336,'At times, his protectiveness of the craft\'s propriety has put him in the uncomfortable position of being \"magic\'s policeman,\" he said. \"One of the reasons that a lot magicians find me—elitist perhaps is the right word—is that most of them grow up with their Uncle Henry producing a nickel from their ear, and I grew up with [expert mid-20th century magicians]                                                                        Dai Vernon                                                                and                                                                        Charlie Miller,                                                                so my standards by nature are really high.\"'),(133193694,13386336,'Born Richard Jay Potash in Brooklyn in 1948, he learned magic from his maternal grandfather and made his television debut at age 7. Wearing a tailcoat, young Ricky turned a guinea pig into a bird. \"Keep your eye on it, because straaange things are going to happen,\" he says in a grainy clip from the TV show, included in a recent documentary film about him titled \"Deceptive Practice.\" '),(133193695,13386336,'After training at the elbow of his mentors, Mr. Jay worked at bars (learning to manipulate beer-soaked cards), as an \"outside talker\" at a carnival and, later, solo in theaters where he performed with his sleeves rolled up. He was known for throwing playing cards with enough speed to bury them in watermelons. He shared a stage with Ike and                                                                        Tina Turner                                                                and                                                                        Timothy Leary,                                                                but eventually found a better fit with jazz artists; opening for rock band the B-52s, he got so mad at hecklers in the front row that he threw cards at them and drew some blood, he recalls.'),(133193696,13386336,'Today, he continues to perform and almost always carries a United States Playing Card Co. deck, which he buys by the dozen. But much of his time is spent researching and writing about history\'s human incongruities. At the book fair, he produced an iPad Mini from his jacket pocket to show his collected etchings of                                                                        Matthew Buchinger,                                                                born in 1674. Though he was under 3 feet tall and had no arms or legs, Buchinger was expert in micrographic calligraphy, trick shooting, hornpiping and other feats. \"He\'s the major guy I\'m interested in in the world,\" said Mr. Jay, who plans to complete a book about Buchinger by the end of the year. '),(133193697,13386336,'At one of his last stops at the book fair, as he checked out an old playbill for a Pittsburgh spiritualist named Madame Leicester, he said \"Good God!\" when he noticed one of his own publications behind glass. \"Jay\'s Journal of Anomalies,\" a collected set of quarterlies he published in the 1990s, was going for $3,000. '),(133193698,13386336,'Before moving on, he reluctantly agreed to inscribe the seller\'s personal copy of his out-of-print book \"Cards as Weapons,\" published in 1974 and featuring an illustration of Mr. Jay with long hair and brandishing a card like a dagger. He said, \"You know what this goes for now on the Internet?\" '),(133193699,13386336,' Write to John Jurgensen at john.jurgensen@wsj.com '),(133193700,13386337,'When the NFL announced that it would be staging its 2014 draft two weeks later than usual this year, most NFL executives and coaches were ready to devour the extra time. For people who spend sleepless months watching anyone who has ever touched a football and trying to figure out if their hips are too stiff, every minute counts.'),(133193701,13386337,'Now the wait is over, the draft is Thursday, and there is only one problem: The extra time is making teams dumber.'),(133193702,13386337,'\"We\'re tired of thinking about it,\" said Buffalo Bills general manager Doug Whaley, who took the unusual step of giving scouts time off rather than the alternative: \"Banging our heads against the wall.\" '),(133193703,13386337,'\"We were ready to go yesterday, so it doesn\'t help us,\" Whaley said. \"And I\'m a firm believer in the saying \"study long, study wrong.\"'),(133193704,13386337,'The NFL draft is known as a workaholic\'s dream. Starting immediately after the previous year\'s draft, teams sift through scouting reports, medical briefs, arrest records and anything else they can find to determine whether a prospect\'s backpedal is too high or his arms are too long. The Arizona Cardinals started with 13,000 prospects, shaved the list to 2,000 using specific criteria, and settled on 120 players they will consider drafting. '),(133193705,13386337,'But this year, many teams have discovered that relentless overthinking has crept in and damaged their ability to properly evaluate players. '),(133193706,13386337,'Blake Bortles, the highly touted Central Florida quarterback, joked on Wednesday that popular opinion has shifted so often recently that some mock drafts have pegged him as a top pick one week, and undraftable the next. No player has fallen farther during the longer evaluation process than Louisville quarterback Teddy Bridgewater, who was regarded as a consensus top-five selection a month ago and is now considered a borderline first-round pick. '),(133193707,13386337,'What have the scouts dug up on Bridgewater? His thin ankles. '),(133193708,13386337,''),(133193709,13386337,'\"You have to be careful that you don\'t stare at the board for too long,\" said San Diego Chargers general manager Tom Telesco. \"There are some times you look up there and all you see are the negatives for each player.\" '),(133193710,13386337,'Making matters worse, improvements in technology are giving coaches and scouts even more time, rendering the classic structure of player evaluation nearly obsolete.                                                                        Dave Caldwell,                                                                the Jacksonville Jaguars\' general manager, said that watching limitless, instantly available game film on mobile devices (a luxury only recently afforded to NFL teams) can lead to thinking yourself out of selecting any player.'),(133193711,13386337,'\"You\'re sitting there saying, \'Am I missing anything? Am I missing anything?\' and your staff is saying the same thing. You have the scout\'s grade, the coaches\' grade, everything checks out and you\'re just saying, \'What are we looking for? Why are we looking at this so hard?\'\"'),(133193712,13386337,'Maybe because they just can\'t help themselves. A majority of NFL teams have been hunkered down in their facilities for these extra two weeks.                                                                        Dennis Hickey,                                                                the Miami Dolphins\' general manager, said he has been watching more film. The New York Jets said they were able to spend more time on player workouts. '),(133193713,13386337,'But other teams have chosen to shut their brains off. Patriots coach Bill Belichick ran a half-marathon in Nashville in two hours, 36 minutes. \"It was a great run,\" he said. Green Bay Packers general manager                                                                        Ted Thompson                                                                said he had all but wrapped up the yearlong process rather than stretch it to Thursday: \"We\'re sitting around with not much to do.\"'),(133193714,13386337,'Meanwhile, the delaying of the draft—which was caused by a scheduling conflict at Radio City Music Hall, where the event has been staged every year since 2006—has led to some discussion over when, and where, it will be held in the future. NFL Commissioner Roger Goodell has heard from multiple cities that want to host the draft, including Chicago and Los Angeles. A decision is expected this summer or fall—that is, if the league doesn\'t get overwhelmed by all the options. '),(133193715,13386337,'\"We will evaluate how well a May draft works in the context of the off-season,\" an NFL spokesman said. \"We will talk to fans, clubs, players and network partners. Everything is on the table—when, where and how many days.\" '),(133193716,13386337,' Write to Kevin Clark at kevin.clark@wsj.com '),(133193717,13386338,'With my nonexistent pick in the 2014 NFL draft, I am taking Johnny Manziel, quarterback, Texas A&M. I know it\'s not the cautious move, but caution is for escalators and cutting bagels at 6 a.m. I\'ve heard the hesitations and qualifiers and skepticism and all the reasons why Johnny Manziel is not a prototypical NFL guy. I\'m not dissuaded. I\'m not feeling prototypical. I\'m taking Johnny Football. '),(133193718,13386338,'Here is Manziel late Wednesday morning, standing in a sunny athletic field in downtown Manhattan, surrounded by cameras and digital recorders, ears of the world waiting, asked if teams that pass on him will come to regret it. '),(133193719,13386338,'\"I believe they will,\" he said. '),(133193720,13386338,'Yes! In a week saturated with safe dull happy talk, how nice it is to hear a prospect skip the safe dull happy talk. The safe dull happy thing for Manziel would be some kind of blahs-ville mush like, \'No, no, no. I have no ill feelings toward anybody. I\'m just happy to go anywhere.\"'),(133193721,13386338,' I believe they will.  '),(133193722,13386338,'Love it. '),(133193723,13386338,''),(133193724,13386338,'Now I know that taking Manziel with my draft pick decisively fails me as a \"football person.\" If I were a \"football person,\" I would not be enticed by such easy draft day catnip. I would be resistant to all the hype and the marketing machinery that has turned an undersized college-football player into a super-celebrity before he has taken a professional snap. I would be concerned about Manziel\'s height and size and his ability to withstand the punishment of an NFL pass rush. I would be concerned about Manziel\'s mechanics. I would be concerned if he could fit into my system.'),(133193725,13386338,'Here\'s my system: Johnny Manziel. '),(133193726,13386338,'Because I have too much Johnny Football in my brain to be turned away by Johnny Football. Every time I turned on a TV last fall, Manziel was doing something on a college-football field I\'d never quite seen on a college-football field. '),(133193727,13386338,'You probably saw the Alabama game last fall. Johnny Manziel and the Texas A&M Aggies beat the Crimson Tide, 42-49. I know technically it was a loss but it felt like something unreal, almost ecstatic. The game had been set up as The Official Comeuppance after Manziel\'s electric Heisman season. What\'s the Big Deal about Johnny Manziel? Manziel marched right out and showed the planet what the big deal was.'),(133193728,13386338,'He\'s unorthodox! He\'s a freelancer! He chucks the ball like he\'s throwing a frozen turkey onto the roof! If I were a good football person, I would turn my attention to other quarterback prospects. Maybe Teddy Bridgewater from Louisville, or Central Florida\'s Blake Bortles. '),(133193729,13386338,'Look at Bortles, he\'s right over there, at this same Play 60 NFL event near the Hudson River. Man is a skyscraper. Six foot five. 230 pounds. Tall, steely-eyed, broad shoulders, quarterback central casting. He looks like the guy who breaks up with Kate Hudson in the first half of a Kate Hudson movie. '),(133193730,13386338,'I don\'t want the guy who breaks up with Kate Hudson in the first half of a Kate Hudson movie. Nothing against Bortles, who very well may thrive in the NFL. I\'m just taking Johnny Football.'),(133193731,13386338,'He is showy, he is cocksure, he is an entertainer. So what? It\'s bizarre to hear the brains behind football dissociate themselves from show business. People: you are having your draft live at Radio City Music Hall. You are show business. '),(133193732,13386338,'Manziel cannot be certain where he will go. Right now he is a rumor inside a rumor inside a rumor. There\'s been the Houston rumor. The St. Louis rumor. The Jacksonville rumor. The Cleveland rumor. The Minnesota rumor, the Tampa Bay rumor, the obligatory Raiders rumor. (There\'s always a Raiders rumor, for everyone—every human, at some point, will be the subject of a Raiders rumor, it\'s the Warholian rule of NFL life and the craziness of the Raiders.)'),(133193733,13386338,'The most delicious rumor, of course, is the Dallas rumor, which is a predictable turn in the beautiful madness that is the Dallas Cowboys, who already have a well-paid celebrity quarterback in Tony Romo. But Dallas is an entertainment company with a side business as a football team.'),(133193734,13386338,'Who knows what Thursday will bring? The lead-up to the draft is comical theater—teams talk themselves in and out of anything; the counterintuitive take becomes the intuitive take; cynicism is cheap and easy to find. Teams know what they want, but the speculation is maddening. I feel like I have been standing behind the Houston Texans in a Starbucks line for four months. '),(133193735,13386338,'If it were me, the decision would be easy. I hope he falls straight to me. This draft I\'m taking Johnny Manziel. Now who is going to give me a pick?'),(133193736,13386338,' Write to Jason Gay at Jason.Gay@wsj.com '),(133193737,13386339,'Without John Isner, American tennis would be in the red.'),(133193738,13386339,'In Madrid on Wednesday, Isner advanced to the round of 16 at the Mutua Madrid Open with a victory that improved his 2014 record on the ATP World Tour to 15-6. Isner, ranked No. 10 in the world, has single-handedly kept American men ranked inside the top 100 from posting an overall losing record this season.'),(133193739,13386339,'Of the seven Americans ranked in the top 100 on the ATP, only Isner and Jack Sock, ranked No. 77, have won more matches than they have lost. The combined record of the American men ranked in the top 100 is 51-48, with one title—won by Isner, of course. Without Isner, the other six are 36-42.'),(133193740,13386339,'It gets worse the further back you look. So far this year, American men in the top 200—including Isner—are a combined 61-76 in ATP matches. '),(133193741,13386339,'But some help could be on the way for the French Open later this month. '),(133193742,13386339,'Robby Ginepri, a 31-year-old who reached No. 15 in the world in 2005, won the U.S. Tennis Association\'s wild card into the French Open by earning the most ranking points in a series of small tournaments. Ginepri, who has twice reached the fourth round in Paris but has been sidelined with a broken elbow, was optimistic. '),(133193743,13386339,'\"I definitely feel like I can do some damage over there,\" he said. '),(133193744,13386339,'Last year, no American man reached the fourth round in Paris.'),(133193745,13386339,'—Tom Perrotta'),(133193746,13386340,'Mentally ill people are substantially less likely to commit a violent crime if they are taking psychiatric medication, according to a large new study of the mentally ill in Sweden.'),(133193747,13386340,'The study, published in the journal The Lancet, comes amid persistent concern about the connection between violence and mental illness, fueled by high-profile mass shootings and crimes committed by people diagnosed with psychiatric disorders. Many mental-health experts say the connection between the two is overblown in the public mind.'),(133193748,13386340,'Previous evidence suggests that people with severe mental illnesses do have an elevated risk of violent behavior, compared with the general population, particularly when they are untreated or are engaged in substance abuse. But there has been limited research on the question of whether taking psychiatric medication helps to reduce violence. At the same time, some mental-health experts express concerns about the side effects of heavy-duty psychiatric medications, relative to their benefit.'),(133193749,13386340,'Antipsychotic drugs, which include Clozaril, Risperdal and Zyprexa, commonly sold as generics, are used to treat schizophrenia and other severe mental illness in which individuals lose touch with reality. Side effects include weight gain, sedation and sexual side effects, which lead many patients to stop taking the drugs. Mood stabilizers, such as the drug known commonly as Depakote, are prescribed for those with conditions including bipolar disorder. The new study suggests that such medicines appear to have the benefit of damping violent behavior.'),(133193750,13386340,'\"It\'s another piece in the jigsaw puzzle that helps you think about the risks and benefits of putting them and keeping them on medication,\" said Seena Fazel, a senior research fellow in clinical science at Oxford University and the first author on the study.'),(133193751,13386340,'Only a minority of patients perpetrate crimes, said Dr. Fazel. \"But even in this minority, it may be to a large extent a modifiable risk.\"'),(133193752,13386340,'The study was funded by the Wellcome Trust, a private U.K. foundation, and several grants from the Swedish government. Dr. Fazel said he has no financial ties with drug makers.'),(133193753,13386340,'Researchers from Oxford and the Karolinska Institute in Stockholm used Swedish national registries to examine more than 80,000 people who were prescribed antipsychotics or mood stabilizers from 2006 to 2009, as well as their psychiatric diagnoses and criminal convictions during the same period. '),(133193754,13386340,'They found a significant 45% drop in convictions for violent crime, such as homicide, assault, robbery or any sexual offense, during periods when the individuals were thought to be taking their medications, based on prescription and dispensing records, regardless of their diagnosis, compared with when they were off meds. Patients diagnosed with bipolar disorder exhibited a 24% decrease in convictions when taking mood stabilizers.'),(133193755,13386340,'The overall rate of violent-crime convictions for men prescribed the drugs was 6.5% in the period, and 1.4% for women. Previous research has shown a four- to six-fold increase in violence among men with severe mental illness, compared to the general population, according to Dr. Fazel.'),(133193756,13386340,'The study couldn\'t determine why the medications reduced violent crimes, but it could be that drugs treated the psychosis itself—by reducing paranoia, for instance—and also provided broader benefits, such as decreasing impulsivity, said Dr. Fazel. In addition, there are questions about whether the results are generalized to other populations outside Sweden. The rates of psychiatric drug use and assaults recorded by the police are similar to those in the U.S., according to Dr. Fazel.'),(133193757,13386340,'Jeffrey Swanson, a professor of psychiatry and behavioral sciences at Duke University who studies mental health and violence, but wasn\'t involved with the current research, called the study a \"strong analysis\" that provides new evidence that the medications commonly used to treat serious mental illnesses can also reduce risk of violent crime in people with these conditions.'),(133193758,13386340,'However, crime and violence are influenced by many factors, and people with mental illness who perpetrate crimes aren\'t typical of the mentally ill or criminals, he said. \"Violence and mental illness are two important and complicated, but different, public-health problems that intersect on their edges,\" said Dr. Swanson.'),(133193759,13386340,' Write to Shirley S. Wang at shirley.wang@wsj.com '),(133193760,13386341,'After being diagnosed with an autoimmune disorder last September,                                                                        Reva Wood                                                                struggled with chronic pain, and then anxiety stemming from chronic pain. To reduce her anxiety, she decided to try something a little unusual: a videogame called SuperBetter that claimed to use science-based challenges to help her manage anxiety. '),(133193761,13386341,'Digital games are gaining notice from some researchers who think they\'re a novel way to address mental health issues like depression and anxiety. SuperBetter is currently the subject of two scientific trials, including a National Institutes of Health-funded experiment that will begin this summer. A paper by the creator of Personal Zen, published in the March edition of Clinical Psychological Science, shows the mobile game can decrease anxiety in some users after 25 minutes of use. '),(133193762,13386341,'  WSJD is the Journal\'s home for tech news, analysis and product reviews. '),(133193763,13386341,'The Department of Veterans Affairs is internally testing whether more gamelike elements will make its PTSDCoach app, released in 2011, more effective for veterans with post-traumatic stress disorder. '),(133193764,13386341,'It might seem surprising that digital games are being investigated to treat serious mental conditions. But \"gamification\" tools like SuperBetter and Personal Zen can increase access to mental health treatment, says                                                                        Carol Landau,                                                                a professor of psychiatry at the Alpert Medical School at Brown University, who specializes in depression treatment. \"But here\'s the caveat: Nothing replaces face-to-face psychotherapy,\" she says. \"Think how it feels to be comparing a real person who\'s listening to you and giving you these skills together, versus a telephone, versus just a game.\" '),(133193765,13386341,'Ms. Wood, 33, who teaches self-defense and violence prevention in Phoenix, credits SuperBetter with creating a structure that helps her complete tasks—what the game calls \"quests\"—that make her feel better. '),(133193766,13386341,'\"It encourages you to do these daily, small steps that overall improve your general physical well-being, and your general outlook,\" says Ms. Wood. For example, studies suggest that getting exercise or talking to friends can help with depression. '),(133193767,13386341,'She says the game helps break those suggestions into tasks—\"go outside for a few minutes\" or \"contact a friend\"—that she can complete, get points for and feel motivated to continue. She discovered the game after hearing about a TED Talk by SuperBetter creator                                                                        Jane McGonigal.                                                               '),(133193768,13386341,'SuperBetter has been shown to decrease depression in one trial. Researcher                                                                        Ann Marie Roepke,                                                                a University of Pennsylvania psychology graduate student, recruited participants online to play the game. She tested them using the 0 to 60 depression scale from the Center for Epidemiologic Studies depression scale. Higher scores indicate more severe symptoms. A score above 16 suggests depression. After one month of playing the game, the depression score of the 31 players decreased by 11.3 points, compared with a control group that didn\'t play the game and whose scores decreased by 4.3 points. (The study wasn\'t funded by SuperBetter or Ms. McGonigal, Ms. Roepke notes.)'),(133193769,13386341,'People with anxiety or depression often obsess over worst-case scenarios, says Ms. McGonigal, director of games research and development at the Institute for the Future, a Palo Alto, Calif.-based research group. In SuperBetter, this negative habit is represented by a character named Madame Esmerelda—a psychic who looks into a crystal ball and sees only the negative. The player must defeat her by challenging her doomsday predictions. This helps people develop skills similar to those taught in cognitive-behavioral therapy, says Ms. McGonigal: \"It can help you notice bad habits or negative thinking patterns that get in the way of you feeling better or stronger.\"'),(133193770,13386341,'Next month, Ms. McGonigal and                                                                        Lise Worthen-Chaudhari,                                                                a professor of physical medicine and rehabilitation at Ohio State University, will test SuperBetter\'s effectiveness on 20 subjects who have had concussions or brain injuries and have been cleared by their doctors to participate. (Studies have shown that concussions can cause depression, Dr. Worthen-Chaudhari says.) '),(133193771,13386341,'In the four-week study, which is funded by a $150,000 grant from the NIH, the subjects will be instructed to play SuperBetter for at least 10 minutes a day, and will be tested on a variety of depression and cognitive scales before and after the study.'),(133193772,13386341,'The games may seem juvenile, but they can make mental health services more accessible, says                                                                        Tracy Dennis,                                                                professor of psychology at Hunter College. Her app, Personal Zen, was released in a beta version this spring. It has players focus their attention on happy faces and ignoring negative ones. '),(133193773,13386341,' In the Clinical Psychological Science study, which was funded by a grant from the NIH, participants who played Personal Zen for 25 minutes and then had to give a speech had less anxiety than a control group. Dr. Dennis, the lead author on the study, acknowledges the games and mobile apps may not be appropriate for everyone.'),(133193774,13386341,'                                                                        Julia Hoffman,                                                                national director of mobile health at the Department of Veterans Affairs\' Mental Health Services, says that while the department is considering adding game aspects to PTSDCoach, the goal isn\'t to replace therapy but to encourage people to seek it.'),(133193775,13386341,'The successfulness of the games may depend upon what type of person you are, say                                                                        Jonna Koivisto                                                                and                                                                        Juho Hamari,                                                                doctoral students at School of Information Sciences at the University of Tampere in Finland. '),(133193776,13386341,'They recently published a review of past studies in Proceedings of the 47th Hawaii International Conference on System Sciences that found people can quickly lose interest in the games. People with \"success-oriented\" personalities who like external validation such as points and badges may benefit more than \"achievement-oriented\" people who may not see the point of the games, they found.'),(133193777,13386341,' Write to Angela Chen at angela.chen@dowjones.com '),(133193778,13386342,'                                                                         François Martindale,                                                                53, the \"Ice Tech\" for the Montreal Canadiens hockey team, on his Zamboni, as told to A.J. Baime: '),(133193779,13386342,'I was raised in Montreal, where everyone is hockey-crazy. In 1994, I answered an ad in the paper for a job driving a Zamboni for the Canadiens. It sounded like a dream job. I grew up watching this hockey team play.'),(133193780,13386342,'The club sent me to a school in Toronto to study ice-making. I still remember my first day driving a Zamboni at the old Montreal Forum. It was awesome! I\'ve since worked my way up to technical services supervisor, which means I\'m in charge of the ice (among other things) at the Bell Centre.'),(133193781,13386342,'I drive an electric Zamboni—the only electric machine in the National Hockey League. [The others are powered by gas, natural gas or propane.] '),(133193782,13386342,'It starts with a key, just like a car. When the Zamboni moves over the ice, it cuts off a layer, washes the surface and lays down hot water [about 160 degrees Fahrenheit], all at the same time. A system of refrigerated pipes under a concrete floor keeps the ice frozen, and it flash-freezes the hot water, making a smooth surface.'),(133193783,13386342,'I like to keep 2 inches of ice in my building.'),(133193784,13386342,'The fans are ecstatic every time they come in, whether it\'s a regular-season game or the Stanley Cup playoffs, which are happening now. You can actually feel the building shake. I just love being a part of it.'),(133193785,13386343,'\"Saturated fat does not cause heart disease\"—or so concluded a big study published in March in the journal Annals of Internal Medicine. How could this be? The very cornerstone of dietary advice for generations has been that the saturated fats in butter, cheese and red meat should be avoided because they clog our arteries. For many diet-conscious Americans, it is simply second nature to opt for chicken over sirloin, canola oil over butter.'),(133193786,13386343,'The new study\'s conclusion shouldn\'t surprise anyone familiar with modern nutritional science, however. The fact is, there has never been solid evidence for the idea that these fats cause disease. We only believe this to be the case because nutrition policy has been derailed over the past half-century by a mixture of personal ambition, bad science, politics and bias. '),(133193787,13386343,'Our distrust of saturated fat can be traced back to the 1950s, to a man named Ancel Benjamin Keys, a scientist at the University of Minnesota. Dr. Keys was formidably persuasive and, through sheer force of will, rose to the top of the nutrition world—even gracing the cover of Time magazine—for relentlessly championing the idea that saturated fats raise cholesterol and, as a result, cause heart attacks.'),(133193788,13386343,'This idea fell on receptive ears because, at the time, Americans faced a fast-growing epidemic. Heart disease, a rarity only three decades earlier, had quickly become the nation\'s No. 1 killer. Even President Dwight D. Eisenhower suffered a heart attack in 1955. Researchers were desperate for answers.'),(133193789,13386343,'As the director of the largest nutrition study to date, Dr. Keys was in an excellent position to promote his idea. The \"Seven Countries\" study that he conducted on nearly 13,000 men in the U.S., Japan and Europe ostensibly demonstrated that heart disease wasn\'t the inevitable result of aging but could be linked to poor nutrition.'),(133193790,13386343,'Critics have pointed out that Dr. Keys violated several basic scientific norms in his study. For one, he didn\'t choose countries randomly but instead selected only those likely to prove his beliefs, including Yugoslavia, Finland and Italy. Excluded were France, land of the famously healthy omelet eater, as well as other countries where people consumed a lot of fat yet didn\'t suffer from high rates of heart disease, such as Switzerland, Sweden and West Germany. The study\'s star subjects—upon whom much of our current understanding of the Mediterranean diet is based—were peasants from Crete, islanders who tilled their fields well into old age and who appeared to eat very little meat or cheese.'),(133193791,13386343,'As it turns out, Dr. Keys visited Crete during an unrepresentative period of extreme hardship after World War II. Furthermore, he made the mistake of measuring the islanders\' diet partly during Lent, when they were forgoing meat and cheese. Dr. Keys therefore undercounted their consumption of saturated fat. Also, due to problems with the surveys, he ended up relying on data from just a few dozen men—far from the representative sample of 655 that he had initially selected. These flaws weren\'t revealed until much later, in a 2002 paper by scientists investigating the work on Crete—but by then, the misimpression left by his erroneous data had become international dogma.'),(133193792,13386343,'In 1961, Dr. Keys sealed saturated fat\'s fate by landing a position on the nutrition committee of the American Heart Association, whose dietary guidelines are considered the gold standard. Although the committee had originally been skeptical of his hypothesis, it issued, in that year, the country\'s first-ever guidelines targeting saturated fats. The U.S. Department of Agriculture followed in 1980.'),(133193793,13386343,'Other studies ensued. A half-dozen large, important trials pitted a diet high in vegetable oil—usually corn or soybean, but not olive oil—against one with more animal fats. But these trials, mainly from the 1970s, also had serious methodological problems. Some didn\'t control for smoking, for instance, or allowed men to wander in and out of the research group over the course of the experiment. The results were unreliable at best. '),(133193794,13386343,'But there was no turning back: Too much institutional energy and research money had already been spent trying to prove Dr. Keys\'s hypothesis. A bias in its favor had grown so strong that the idea just started to seem like common sense. As Harvard nutrition professor Mark Hegsted said in 1977, after successfully persuading the U.S. Senate to recommend Dr. Keys\'s diet for the entire nation, the question wasn\'t whether Americans should change their diets, but why not? Important benefits could be expected, he argued. And the risks? \"None can be identified,\" he said.'),(133193795,13386343,'In fact, even back then, other scientists were warning about the diet\'s potential unintended consequences. Today, we are dealing with the reality that these have come to pass.'),(133193796,13386343,'One consequence is that in cutting back on fats, we are now eating a lot more carbohydrates—at least 25% more since the early 1970s. Consumption of saturated fat, meanwhile, has dropped by 11%, according to the best available government data. Translation: Instead of meat, eggs and cheese, we\'re eating more pasta, grains, fruit and starchy vegetables such as potatoes. Even seemingly healthy low-fat foods, such as yogurt, are stealth carb-delivery systems, since removing the fat often requires the addition of fillers to make up for lost texture—and these are usually carbohydrate-based.'),(133193797,13386343,'The problem is that carbohydrates break down into glucose, which causes the body to release insulin—a hormone that is fantastically efficient at storing fat. Meanwhile, fructose, the main sugar in fruit, causes the liver to generate triglycerides and other lipids in the blood that are altogether bad news. Excessive carbohydrates lead not only to obesity but also, over time, to Type 2 diabetes and, very likely, heart disease. '),(133193798,13386343,'The real surprise is that, according to the best science to date, people put themselves at higher risk for these conditions no matter what kind of carbohydrates they eat. Yes, even unrefined carbs. Too much whole-grain oatmeal for breakfast and whole-grain pasta for dinner, with fruit snacks in between, add up to a less healthy diet than one of eggs and bacon, followed by fish. The reality is that fat doesn\'t make you fat or diabetic. Scientific investigations going back to the 1950s suggest that actually, carbs do. '),(133193799,13386343,'The second big unintended consequence of our shift away from animal fats is that we\'re now consuming more vegetable oils. Butter and lard had long been staples of the American pantry until Crisco, introduced in 1911, became the first vegetable-based fat to win wide acceptance in U.S. kitchens. Then came margarines made from vegetable oil and then just plain vegetable oil in bottles. '),(133193800,13386343,'All of these got a boost from the American Heart Association—which Procter & Gamble, the maker of Crisco oil, coincidentally helped launch as a national organization. In 1948, P&G made the AHA the beneficiary of the popular \"Walking Man\" radio contest, which the company sponsored. The show raised $1.7 million for the group and transformed it (according to the AHA\'s official history) from a small, underfunded professional society into the powerhouse that it remains today. '),(133193801,13386343,'After the AHA advised the public to eat less saturated fat and switch to vegetable oils for a \"healthy heart\" in 1961, Americans changed their diets. Now these oils represent 7% to 8% of all calories in our diet, up from nearly zero in 1900, the biggest increase in consumption of any type of food over the past century.'),(133193802,13386343,'This shift seemed like a good idea at the time, but it brought many potential health problems in its wake. In those early clinical trials, people on diets high in vegetable oil were found to suffer higher rates not only of cancer but also of gallstones. And, strikingly, they were more likely to die from violent accidents and suicides. Alarmed by these findings, the National Institutes of Health convened researchers several times in the early 1980s to try to explain these \"side effects,\" but they couldn\'t. (Experts now speculate that certain psychological problems might be related to changes in brain chemistry caused by diet, such as fatty-acid imbalances or the depletion of cholesterol.)'),(133193803,13386343,'We\'ve also known since the 1940s that when heated, vegetable oils create oxidation products that, in experiments on animals, lead to cirrhosis of the liver and early death. For these reasons, some midcentury chemists warned against the consumption of these oils, but their concerns were allayed by a chemical fix: Oils could be rendered more stable through a process called hydrogenation, which used a catalyst to turn them from oils into solids. '),(133193804,13386343,'From the 1950s on, these hardened oils became the backbone of the entire food industry, used in cakes, cookies, chips, breads, frostings, fillings, and frozen and fried food. Unfortunately, hydrogenation also produced trans fats, which since the 1970s have been suspected of interfering with basic cellular functioning and were recently condemned by the Food and Drug Administration for their ability to raise our levels of \"bad\" LDL cholesterol. '),(133193805,13386343,'Yet paradoxically, the drive to get rid of trans fats has led some restaurants and food manufacturers to return to using regular liquid oils—with the same long-standing oxidation problems. These dangers are especially acute in restaurant fryers, where the oils are heated to high temperatures over long periods. '),(133193806,13386343,'The past decade of research on these oxidation products has produced a sizable body of evidence showing their dramatic inflammatory and oxidative effects, which implicates them in heart disease and other illnesses such as Alzheimer\'s. Other newly discovered potential toxins in vegetable oils, called monochloropropane diols and glycidol esters, are now causing concern among health authorities in Europe.'),(133193807,13386343,'In short, the track record of vegetable oils is highly worrisome—and not remotely what Americans bargained for when they gave up butter and lard.'),(133193808,13386343,'Cutting back on saturated fat has had especially harmful consequences for women, who, due to hormonal differences, contract heart disease later in life and in a way that is distinct from men. If anything, high total cholesterol levels in women over 50 were found early on to be associated with longer life. This counterintuitive result was first discovered by the famous Framingham study on heart-disease risk factors in 1971 and has since been confirmed by other research. '),(133193809,13386343,'Since women under 50 rarely get heart disease, the implication is that women of all ages have been worrying about their cholesterol levels needlessly. Yet the Framingham study\'s findings on women were omitted from the study\'s conclusions. And less than a decade later, government health officials pushed their advice about fat and cholesterol on all Americans over age 2—based exclusively on data from middle-aged men.'),(133193810,13386343,'Sticking to these guidelines has meant ignoring growing evidence that women on diets low in saturated fat actually increase their risk of having a heart attack. The \"good\" HDL cholesterol drops precipitously for women on this diet (it drops for men too, but less so). The sad irony is that women have been especially rigorous about ramping up on their fruits, vegetables and grains, but they now suffer from higher obesity rates than men, and their death rates from heart disease have reached parity.'),(133193811,13386343,'Seeing the U.S. population grow sicker and fatter while adhering to official dietary guidelines has put nutrition authorities in an awkward position. Recently, the response of many researchers has been to blame \"Big Food\" for bombarding Americans with sugar-laden products. No doubt these are bad for us, but it is also fair to say that the food industry has simply been responding to the dietary guidelines issued by the AHA and USDA, which have encouraged high-carbohydrate diets and until quite recently said next to nothing about the need to limit sugar. '),(133193812,13386343,'Indeed, up until 1999, the AHA was still advising Americans to reach for \"soft drinks,\" and in 2001, the group was still recommending snacks of \"gum-drops\" and \"hard candies made primarily with sugar\" to avoid fatty foods. '),(133193813,13386343,'Our half-century effort to cut back on the consumption of meat, eggs and whole-fat dairy has a tragic quality. More than a billion dollars have been spent trying to prove Ancel Keys\'s hypothesis, but evidence of its benefits has never been produced. It is time to put the saturated-fat hypothesis to bed and to move on to test other possible culprits for our nation\'s health woes.'),(133193814,13386343,' Ms. Teicholz has been researching dietary fat and disease for nearly a decade. Her book, \"The Big Fat Surprise: Why Butter, Meat and Cheese Belong in a Healthy Diet,\" will be published by Simon & Schuster on May 13. '),(133193815,13386344,' THE LAST TIME I was in Tokyo, I made an excursion to the Nihonbashi branch of                                                                          Takashimaya,                                   8233.TO +2.51%                                      Takashimaya Co. Ltd.                                   Japan: Tokyo                                                ¥982                                                +24                 +2.51%                                                        May 8, 2014 3:00 pm                                                  Volume :                   1.25M                                                                                                       P/E Ratio                 17.31                                       Market Cap             ¥316.93 Billion                                                                   Dividend Yield               1.02%                                        Rev. per Employee               ¥115,476,000                                                                                                                                   05/01/14 How Japan Has Perfected Hospit...             04/11/14 Tokyo Shares Tumble to 2014 Lo...             02/09/14 Chocolate or Flowers on Valent...             More quote details and news »                                                             8233.TO in                                                                                                                          Your Value                 Your Change                                                                                                                                                                 Short position                                                                                                                    a chain of department stores founded in 1831, because a friend told me to ride the elevators. Architecturally, the elevators aren\'t anything special—the building dates to 1933, and it looks like other grand department stores from that era. But it\'s staffed by employees so attentive and polite that they transform the act of moving between floors from a mundane, even annoying, task into a pageant of ritualized courtesy.'),(133193816,13386344,'It starts as you approach the elevator bank. An attendant in the well-tailored uniform of a 1960s stewardess (jacket, skirt, gloves, pumps, jaunty hat) welcomes you with a series of bows and spoken greetings that continue, without pause, as she pushes the call button and directs you to the arriving elevator with an arm held at a perfect 90-degree angle. When the elevator door opens, an operator—dressed like a stewardess from a competing airline (different color jacket)—welcomes you with more bows and greetings. This is when the display of politeness turns into a delicate series of choreographed movements: You step into the elevator; the operator pivots and extends her arm to protect you from the closing grate; and the attendant in the lobby turns to face you and bows deeply, holding the position with practiced stillness. Third floor, please.'),(133193817,13386344,'Is it too much? Maybe. The bowing and gesturing might be unnecessary—if you\'ve made it to Tokyo, you know how to work an elevator—but it sends a message: From the moment you walk in the door, the employees are completely attuned to you. '),(133193818,13386344,'Before I went to Japan for the first time, I was told by well-traveled friends to expect a level of customer service so polished and comprehensive that even the most basic transactions can take on a ceremonious air. But that\'s like somebody telling you what it\'s like to drive loops on the Nürburgring Nordschleife test track or watch a Big Sur sunset: It\'s just words until it happens to you. '),(133193819,13386344,'Even though I was impressed with Japanese civility from the moment my passport was stamped at Narita airport, I didn\'t fully appreciate the extent of the country\'s service culture until I was partway through a multicourse meal at Ishikawa, a small Tokyo restaurant with three Michelin stars. I was sitting at the counter, directly opposite chef Hideki Ishikawa. At times he explained to me what he was preparing, but he left other dishes to my waitress, who spoke excellent English. After asking her a quick question, I noticed that she kneeled before answering. In fact, she always kneeled before speaking. She wore a slim-fitting kimono, and when she lowered herself she gracefully corkscrewed her body so that her knees settled on the ground without her needing to steady herself.'),(133193820,13386344,'I felt awful—and elated. What a wrong, beautiful manner in which to be guided through dinner. At the end of the meal she, Ishikawa and what seemed like the rest of the staff escorted me to the sidewalk. They stood in a line and bowed. At the end of the block, I glanced over my shoulder. They were still in formation, and when they saw me turn they bowed again.'),(133193821,13386344,'\"You have a three-star restaurant in Japan, the famous chef with all the awards—and he\'s not only preparing the food, he\'s preparing it for you,\" says                                                                        David Kinch,                                                                the chef and owner at Manresa, in Los Gatos, California. Kinch, who once worked in Japan, returns at least once a year, and he tells me that my meal at Ishikawa is how it\'s done in Japan. \"He actually hands it to you. He asks you, \'How are you? Are you enjoying it? Is it to your liking?\' It\'s a sense of hospitality that comes across as genuine, not as part of a training program,\" says Kinch. '),(133193822,13386344,'Just as important, you don\'t pay extra for that care. There is no tipping in Japan. It\'s not only discouraged, it\'s simply not done. There\'s no tip line on a credit card slip, and if you try to press cash into the hand of someone opening your door or taking your coat, the person will look as confused as your dentist would if you tried to slip him or her $20 for being so generous with the Novocaine.'),(133193823,13386344,'The service culture of Japan, which always over-delivers, directly contradicts the tipping culture of the United States, which supposedly incentivizes superior service but can have exactly the inverse effect: Tip well, or watch out. \"You have to remember that in Japan you don\'t have a category called service, because it\'s completely integrated into what you do,\" says Merry White, author of Coffee Life in Japan and professor of anthropology at Boston University. \"It\'s not an extra. It\'s valued, but it isn\'t monetized.\"'),(133193824,13386344,'         “         \"You have a three-star restaurant in Japan, the famous chef with all the awards—and he\'s not only preparing the food, he\'s preparing it for you.\"         ”       '),(133193825,13386344,'I find the Japanese system liberating. The price is the price, and if you are treated well it\'s not because you\'re expected to pay extra. \"We [in America] are the ones who separate it out,\" White notes. The service I experienced in Japan wasn\'t simply a better version of what I find in the United States and Europe, it was the expression of a profoundly different understanding of what we consider \"work.\"'),(133193826,13386344,'A job means more than just checking off a couple of boxes. According to Masaru Watanabe, the executive director and general manager of the Palace Hotel Tokyo, a grand hotel overlooking the grounds of the Imperial Palace, it demands an emotional commitment. \"Although Japanese hospitality, or what we call omotenashi, has developed a reputation outside of Japan as being a benchmark for exceptional service, it can be very difficult to define. It\'s as intangible as it is palpable, something to be felt rather than explained,\" says Watanabe. \"To me, [it is] hospitality that\'s extended with the utmost sincerity, grace and respect, however big or small the gesture or the task. Not to be mistaken with the other, perhaps more commonly experienced version of service, which is superficial service delivered out of a sense of obligation and with an expectation of reward.\"'),(133193827,13386344,'I experienced that one night when I went for a nightcap at the New York Bar on the top floor of the Park Hyatt Tokyo, where I was staying. The staff reopened the bar—even though it was well after last call—because it was my birthday. How did they know? My mother had a cake delivered to my room earlier, and it seemed the entire hotel was notified. Looking out over the blinking red lights that punctuate the Tokyo skyline, with a long pour of a Yamazaki single malt, I thought about what might have happened at a similar hotel in London or Paris: I would have been given a courteous but firm no, possibly offered a glass of Champagne in the lobby or my room. It\'s a safe bet the hotel wouldn\'t have reopened its marquee bar for one last $14 whisky. '),(133193828,13386344,'According to White, what I experienced at the Park Hyatt Tokyo was an example of omoiyari. \"It means the active sensitivity to other people,\" she tells me. \"It anticipates the needs and desires of other people. It\'s not broad-brush, it\'s fine-tuned.\" White explains that omoiyari is taught to children and praised in school. When the staff reopened the bar for me, it was because they could tell it would make me happy to play out my Lost in Translation fantasy. '),(133193829,13386344,'And it\'s more than just an expression of national character. \"There are real institutional reasons why service is so good,\" says Amy Borovoy, associate professor of East Asian studies at Princeton University. \"Sociologists call it stakeholder capitalism versus shareholder capitalism,\" she continues. \"In the United States you have shareholder capitalism, in which shareholders will pressure a company for short-term profits. Japan and Germany have a stakeholder system, which lets companies invest in workers who are better trained, more loyal and more informed.\"'),(133193830,13386344,'You find loyal, informed workers even in the most modest settings. \"I believe that the world\'s best McDonald\'s service is in Japan,\" says Tokyo-based book editor Masanobu Sugatsuke. \"The same goes for Starbucks. No staff sighs during work and there is no extensive chatting between co-workers,\" he adds, describing the reverse of almost every McDonald\'s and Starbucks in the United States. '),(133193831,13386344,'I found omotenashi in a municipal agency that rented bicycles for what worked out to 85 cents a day. I walked down a flight of stairs into a windowless storage room located under the sidewalk and was greeted by an elderly gentleman who welcomed me, carefully went over the contract, then personally checked the wheels, gears, brakes, handlebars and seat before escorting me to the street. The attendant wasn\'t being servile or obsequious or overly concerned by my obvious foreignness. When he bowed and wished me well with what seemed like heartfelt sincerity, he was being professional.'),(133193832,13386345,' THIS MONTH, after a two-year, $40 million renovation, the Metropolitan Museum of Art unveils its Costume Institute\'s revamped galleries, newly christened the                                                                          Anna Wintour                                                                Costume Center, with an inaugural show dedicated to master couturier                                                                          Charles James.                                                                '),(133193833,13386345,'James occupies an almost saintly position in the fashion world—Cristóbal Balenciaga called him \"the world\'s best and only dressmaker\"—but it was not merely his stature or influence that led curator-in-charge                                                                        Harold Koda                                                                to select him as the crown jewel for the institute\'s renovation. The show\'s title, \"Charles James: Beyond Fashion,\" is an allusion to the scientific approach and mathematical tailoring that underpin James\'s famously sculptural designs—\"So much of what he did was antithetical to the physics of fabric,\" says Koda—making him the perfect match for the newfound center\'s technological prowess. '),(133193834,13386345,'Visitors to the 4,200-square-foot space will have the opportunity to hear recordings of James\'s voice and see three-dimensional projections that reveal interior layers of the roughly 70 garments on display—all via a new sound system and advanced video technology. X-ray images will display the complex inner structure of the designer\'s midcentury ball gowns, whose foundations of millinery blocking net, willow and buckram can weigh up to 12 pounds. Thanks to James\'s rigorous approach and detailed knowledge of anatomy, the voluminous, architectural dresses—worn by socialites like Millicent Rogers and Dominique de Menil—felt nearly weightless.'),(133193835,13386345,'The center\'s state-of-the-art additions extend beyond the main gallery to a new conservation lab, equipped with wide doors to accommodate large gowns, a wet lab for treating fabrics and a fume-extraction unit. There\'s also an updated storage system to handle the museum\'s collection of more than 35,000 costumes and accessories, sourced from five continents and dating back to the 16th century.'),(133193836,13386345,'These changes mark the first major modernization of the museum\'s fashion wing since 1992. Originally opened as an independent entity in 1937, it merged with the Met in 1946 and came into its own as a curatorial showcase in the 1970s under the supervision of legendary Vogue editor                                                                        Diana Vreeland.                                                                Incorporating music, lighting and props, Vreeland transformed the sleepy department into a theatrical platform for lavish, visually rich exhibitions such as \"The World of Balenciaga\" and \"The Glory of Russian Costume,\" redefining what such exhibitions could be and sparking unprecedented boosts in attendance. Current Vogue editor in chief (and Condé Nast\'s artistic director) Anna Wintour has played a similarly active role, raising approximately $125 million for the institute and revamping its annual gala from a garden-variety fund-raiser into a glamorous red-carpet event that attracts Hollywood celebrities and fashion-world luminaries. Following the Brooklyn Museum\'s transfer of its costume collection in 2009 (they supplied much of the Charles James materials), the institute is now home to one of the largest and most comprehensive costume collections in the world.'),(133193837,13386345,'In recent years, the Costume Institute has hosted some of the museum\'s most popular and successful exhibitions. \"Alexander McQueen: Savage Beauty\" in 2011 was one of the top 10 most visited ever; membership doubled from the previous year, and the show was extended a week due to public demand and caused the museum to stay open until midnight for the first time in its history. '),(133193838,13386345,'What excites the institute\'s curators now are the center\'s versatile facilities, built to accommodate quick transitions between shows. \"The idea behind it was to create a more tabula rasa place,\" says Costume Institute curator Andrew Bolton, a \"white cube\" that will allow the museum to create \"more conceptual\" exhibitions. Bolton is considering a multimedia installation that would explore the sounds generated by fabrics. \"I always wanted to do a show called \'The Rustle of the Bustle,\'\" he quips. Another idea Bolton and Koda have discussed is aiming digital projections at mannequins to explore the changing silhouette of men\'s suits over time.'),(133193839,13386345,'Met director                                                                        Thomas P. Campbell                                                                is pursuing digital technology as a means to bring collections to life throughout the museum, a larger trend within the industry. Maddy Burke-Vigeland, a principal with New York\'s Gensler design firm, says technology is helping turn museum exhibits into a kind of \"hyperreality\" by blurring the distinction between performing arts and traditional displays. \"It\'s the idea of intensifying the viewer experience,\" she says.'),(133193840,13386345,'In its new capacity, the Costume Institute will eventually extend its exhibition season to 10 months a year and plans to mount two to three shows annually, interspersed with smaller displays drawn from the permanent collection. Bolton has long dreamed of doing a \"Freud and Fashion\" show, which would bring a psychoanalytic perspective to fashion. '),(133193841,13386345,'The curators intend to sponsor more collaborations like the 2012 exhibition on designers                                                                        Miuccia Prada                                                                and Elsa Schiaparelli, for which filmmaker Baz Luhrmann filmed Prada in imaginary conversation with Schiaparelli, played by actress Judy Davis. They also plan to reach out to other artists—such as Sofia Coppola,                                                                        Nick Knight                                                                and Chris Cunningham—with innovative approaches to storytelling and technology. '),(133193842,13386345,'The institute has in many ways mirrored the changing perceptions of fashion through time, and the redesign above all promises to add new dimensions to the public\'s understanding of the creation of a piece of clothing—a process that can be as complex as painting or sculpture. \"Fashion is an art form,\" says Bolton. \"That\'s what we want to show.\" '),(133193843,13386346,'It\'s been nearly 40 years since                                                                        Steven Spurrier,                                                                a British wine merchant working in Paris, held a blind tasting between the top wines of California and their French counterparts. The \"Judgment of Paris,\" as it became known, surprised many, as a clutch of Californian wines scored higher than examples from Bordeaux and Burgundy. Overnight the world woke up to what Californian winemakers had known all along: Their wines could stand alongside the very best.'),(133193844,13386346,'In many ways the late 1970s were a turning point for California wines, as key figures like Robert Mondavi,                                                                        Paul Draper                                                                of Ridge Vineyards, Chateau Montelena winemaker                                                                        Mike Grgich,                                                                and Joe and                                                                        Alice Heitz                                                                took an industry that had been best known for producing high-volume standard table wine and planted it firmly on the fine wine map.'),(133193845,13386346,''),(133193846,13386346,'But then something happened. In his book \"The New California Wine,\"                                                                        Jon Bonné                                                                argues that after the 1970s the state\'s wines began to evolve into a richer, riper style. What had originally impressed the judges in Paris—Cabernet Sauvignon and Chardonnay made with an emphasis on structure, freshness and fruit—was sacrificed for a style that favored power and immediate impact. '),(133193847,13386346,'When it comes to the complicated world of wine, broad-brush generalizations are never wise. And it\'s worth bearing in mind that California is the fourth largest producer of wine in the world—it\'s huge. From its valleys and vineyards come myriad wines, from Blossom Hill to Opus One. And, as                                                                        Mike Steinberger                                                                recently wrote on wine-searcher.com, the pursuit of finesse is hardly a recent or revolutionary development in California.'),(133193848,13386346,'I remember as a young wine merchant in the mid-1990s tasting wines such as Calera Pinot Noir,                                                                        Jim Clendenen\'s                                                                Au Bon Climat and Chalk Hill\'s Cabernet Sauvignon, and being struck by their Old World charm. '),(133193849,13386346,'But Mr. Bonné is right when he says there was a style change in the 1980s. You could taste it, see it on the label as the alcohol percentage increased, and read about it in specialist wine magazines as the latest viticultural developments (particularly picking the grapes later, and thus riper) became more widespread.'),(133193850,13386346,'The change in emphasis wasn\'t necessarily a bad thing. But European tastes tend to favor freshness and purity of fruit, and for some the wines became a bit of a turnoff. My own view is perhaps more nuanced: I prefer lighter, fresher and more vibrant wines, but there is room for both styles to flourish. A quick word of warning, though: Rich, jammy, oaky wines can be easy to taste (and so they often get good reviews) but they can be difficult to drink, especially with food, as their strong flavor can dominate the palate.'),(133193851,13386346,'         “         Overnight the world woke up to what Californian winemakers had known all along         ”       '),(133193852,13386346,'The good news is that for those who prefer the fresher style there is now a generation of young California winemakers providing just that. In his book, Mr. Bonné has unearthed a few. Wineries such as Lioco, Arnot-Roberts, Broc Cellars, Corison, Viano vineyards, Tatomer Wines and Domaine de la Côte may not be as famous as Ridge or Heitz but they are producing wines with a fine, fresh, mineral structure. Vine Starr Zinfandel, by                                                                        Chris Brockway                                                                of Broc Cellars, is a magical wine, as far removed from the big confected style of Zinfandel as you can get. '),(133193853,13386346,'When I caught up with Mr. Brockway at a recent tasting, I asked him how he\'d achieved such a refined style. He put it down to picking his grapes early to avoid overripeness and minimal intervention in the cellar, leaving the grapes to speak for themselves.'),(133193854,13386346,'Furthermore he told me he wanted to make wines that one could pair with food and were refreshing to drink. It was music to my ears. As Mr. Spurrier said: \"For the first time in many years I want to fill my cellar with Californian wine.\"'),(133193855,13386346,'—Find one-minute wine reviews and more at  WSJ.com/vintage . Email Will at william.lyons@wsj.com or follow him on Twitter: @Will_Lyons '),(133193856,13386347,'Moni pohtii näin keväällä, milloin oma kesäloma kannattaisi pitää. Milloin olisivat mahdollisimman hyvät säät?'),(133193857,13386347,'IS tutki Ilmatieteen laitoksen tilastojen perusteella suurten kaupunkien kesäsäitä vuosien 1981-2010 väliltä. Tutkimuksessa ilmeni, että paras kesälomaviikko ajoittuu heinäkuun toiselle viikolle, kun tutkimuksen mittareina käytettiin lämpötilaa, sademäärää ja auringon vuorokautisia paistetunteja. Säähavaintoja tutkittiin seitsemän päivän jaksoissa kesä- ja elokuun välisenä aikana. Koko tilaston löydät jutun alta.'),(133193858,13386347,'Esimerkiksi opettajilla ei ole viikkojen valinnan suhteen ongelmaa, kun lomaa kestää lähes koko kesän. Yrittäjille loman pitäminen ei sen sijaan ole mikään itsestään selvyys.'),(133193859,13386347,'Sopivan sauman löytäminen loman pitämiselle on kiinni muista asioista kuin säästä.'),(133193860,13386347,'- Jos on esimerkiksi kunnossapitoalalla tai vastaavalla, niin heinäkuuhan on parasta työaikaa. Tämäntyyppiselle ammatinharjoittajalle joku syyskuu tai marraskuu voisi olla siinä mielessä hyvä ajankohta lomalle. Mutta jos ajatellaan vaikka lakimiestä tai parturi-kampaajaa, niin mikä ettei heinäkuun toinen viikko voisi olla heille hyvää aikaa lomailla, Suomen Pienyrittäjien puheenjohtaja Harri Jyrkiäinen miettii.'),(133193861,13386347,'Toinen juttu on se, pystyykö yrittäjä ylipäätään lomailemaan. Jyrkiäisen mukaan osa pienyrittäjistä pystyy pitämään kesällä \"ihan kohtuullisen loman\", mutta valtaosa ei minkäänlaista. Jos kassa ei kilise, ei ole tulojakaan. Jyrkiäinen toimii itsekin yrittäjänä puheenjohtajantoimensa ohella.'),(133193862,13386347,'- Kyllä sen viikon loman löytäminen mihin tahansa vuodenaikaan vaatii omat järjestelynsä. Saattaisin kuvitella, että heinäkuussa tulee yksi viikko pidettyä. Se voisi olla se heinäkuun toinen viikko tai sitten kolmas, Jyrkiäinen sanoo.'),(133193863,13386347,'\"Kesän sää'),(133193864,13386347,'on arvaamaton\"'),(133193865,13386347,'Forecan meteorologi Juha Föhr suhtautuu hyvin pessimistisesti kesän sään ennustamiseen. Tai oikeastaan hän ei halua lähteä vielä edes ennustamaan tulevan kesän säätä.'),(133193866,13386347,'- En minä tiedä, miten tämän kesän sää muotoutuu. Minä haluaisin nähdä ihmisen, joka pystyy sanomaan faktana, millainen kesä tulee. Tieteelliseltä pohjalta ennustetta ei voi vielä tehdä. Mutta kukin uskoo, mihin uskoo. Voihan ennustetta kysyä pajunvarsiukoilta. Tai osa ennustaa almanakoista ja planeetoista. Kyllä näitä riittää, Föhr lataa.'),(133193867,13386347,'Hieman rauhoituttuaan Föhr lupaa kuitenkin hieman kuvailla suomalaista kesää.'),(133193868,13386347,'- Koko kesän ehdoton ydin on se, että sää voi vaihdella päivästä ja viikosta toiseen. Kesän sää on arvaamaton. Se on erittäin suurella todennäköisyydellä lämpimämpi kuin talvi. Lämpimämpi kuin yksikään muu vuodenaika, Föhr muotoilee.'),(133193869,13386347,'Hän itse nauttii erityisesti loppukesästä.'),(133193870,13386347,'- Pidän samettisesta ja pehmeästä lämmöstä. Loppukesässä on hyvää se, kun on pimeät, mutta lämpimät illat. En pidä siitä, kun aurinko ei laske, minkä takia pimennysverhoja joutuu koko ajan käyttämään. Minä en suostu nukkumaan huoneessa, jota ei saa pimeäksi, Föhr kommentoi.'),(133193871,13386347,'Klikkaa alla olevaa taulukkoa, niin näet sen suurempana!'),(133193872,13386348,'Pääkaupungissa Mexicossa korkeat rakennukset huojuivat ja ihmiset ryntäsivät turvaan kaduille.'),(133193873,13386348,'Järistyksen keskus oli Meksikon etelärannikolla Guerreron osavaltiossa.'),(133193874,13386348,'KUVA: HENRY ROMERO   Poistumisreitti rakennuksesta kulki portaita pitkin.'),(133193875,13386348,'KUVA: HENRY ROMERO   Mexico Cityssä paettiin maanjäristystä taloista kaduille.'),(133193876,13386349,'- Tappiot auttavat kehittymään ihmisenä, Rehn kuittasi menneet vaalitappionsa Ilta-Sanomien eurovaaliväittelyn aluksi.'),(133193877,13386349,'Tappiota ei tällä kertaa tullut. Rehn voitti Li Anderssonin (vas) yleisöäänin 72-28.'),(133193878,13386349,'Suurin erimielisyys väittelijöiden välille aiheutui eurokriisin hoitokeinoista. Andersson pitää EU:n velkajärjestelyjä alusta asti epäonnistuneina. Hän olisi laittanut pankit ja finanssialan suurempaan vastuuseen kriisinhoidossa. Rehn taas puolustaa eurokriisin hoidossa tehtyjä ratkaisuja.'),(133193879,13386349,'- Kun aloitin talouskomissaarina, talous oli vapaassa pudotuksessa. Nyt Irlanti ja Espanja ovat lähteneet normaalin rahoituksen piirin, Portugali tekee pian samoin, Rehn summasi.'),(133193880,13386349,'Hän uskoo myös \"hidastelijamaiden\" Kreikan, Italian ja Ranskan nousevan.'),(133193881,13386349,'- Pahin on ohitse, sanoi Rehn.'),(133193882,13386349,'Rehn uskoo, että talouden elpyminen on käynnissä EU:n alueella ja työllisyys nousussa. Rehn haluaisi rakenteellisia uudistuksia, joilla vahvistaa eurooppalaista yritystoimintaa.'),(133193883,13386349,'Elvytystä'),(133193884,13386349,'eri keinoin'),(133193885,13386349,'Väittelijät jatkaisivat molemmat kriisin elvytystä, mutta eri keinoin. Andersson parantaisi palkansaajien ostovoimaa julkisilla investoinneilla, Rehn taas tukemalla yrittäjyyttä. Andersson on myös tuohtunut sosiaaliturvan heikentämisestä.'),(133193886,13386349,'- Kreikkalaisten mahdollisuuksia maksaa takaisin on vaikeutettu. Käytetäänkö velkaa työllisyyden parantamiseen? Valtio velkaantuu ja vyön kiristys heikentää ostovoimaa, en näe tässä mitään järkeä, sanoi Andersson.'),(133193887,13386349,'- Monet ongelmista johtuvat sääntöjen noudattamattomuudesta. On jouduttu tekemään palomiehen ja arkkitehdin hommia yhtä aikaa, Rehn vastasi.'),(133193888,13386349,'Keskustelua'),(133193889,13386349,'Kreikan kuripaketista'),(133193890,13386349,'Rehnin mukaan myös vasemmistoliitto on osaltaan vastuussa ankarasta talouskurista, sillä se oli hallituksessa.'),(133193891,13386349,'- Euroopan komissio vaikuttaa pehmoilijalta verrattuna Suomen hallitukseen, jossa vasemmistoliittokin oli mukana tekemässä kurilinjaa, Rehn tuumasi.'),(133193892,13386349,'Anderssonin mielestä kokoomus oli enemmän vastuussa päätöksenteosta.'),(133193893,13386349,'- Vasemmistoliitto on yrittänyt ajaa inhimillistä linjaa hallituksessa.'),(133193894,13386350,'Mention you\'ve got a picky eater to a fellow parent, and the choruses of \"me too!\" come quick. Some fed-up parents—embarrassed, at their wits\' end or worried about their children\'s nutrition—are hiring picky-eater coaches to expand their kids\' palates.'),(133193895,13386350,'Leslie Springer was tired of acting like a short-order cook for her twin girls in second grade and daughter in preschool. Day-Glo orange mac and cheese was a staple. Snacks consisted of Goldfish crackers, Cheez-Its, potato chips and Oreos. Her girls devoured french fries but wouldn\'t touch other kinds of potatoes. She would offer cauliflower and carrots only to get rebuffed.'),(133193896,13386350,'Ms. Springer sought help from food coach                                                                        Tara Roscioli,                                                                who had recently begun a Fit Moms group in New Jersey geared at encouraging healthier choices for mothers. Ms. Roscioli suggested some initial substitutions: steel-cut oats with a pinch of brown sugar and raisins instead of heavily presweetened oatmeal packets. Brown rice instead of white rice. Apple chips instead of potato chips.'),(133193897,13386350,'\"When Tara suggested this, I thought, \'This is never going to happen,\' \" says Ms. Springer, a clinical social worker in Maplewood, N.J.'),(133193898,13386350,'But it did happen. Nadia, one of the twins, has grown to love sweet potatoes. Quinoa regularly makes an appearance on the dinner table. To coax them to eat it, Ms. Springer includes olives, which she knows they like. Juice used to be her daughters\' drink of choice, but Ms. Springer has replaced it with water or seltzer with just a hint of juice. '),(133193899,13386350,'\"There was protest in the beginning, but then it just became the norm,\" she says.'),(133193900,13386350,'The key, she learned from Ms. Roscioli, is mixing familiar foods with unfamiliar ones and involving the children in prep work. In a cooking class Ms. Roscioli held for Ms. Springer and her daughters, they learned to make homemade granola and ice cream from frozen bananas with a splash of coconut milk. '),(133193901,13386350,'\"Getting kids involved in the kitchen is a huge part of it,\" says Ms. Roscioli.'),(133193902,13386350,'Reforming picky eaters isn\'t cheap. Fees and approaches vary—some coaches interview parents over the phone and offer counsel; others like to meet the children. An initial hourlong consultation can cost up to $250, plus follow-up visits. Coaches say they are able to resolve most instances of overly discerning young eaters for about $400.'),(133193903,13386350,'Getting more selective about food is developmentally typical and happens to most children by age 2 or so as they start experimenting with autonomy and control. A parent\'s job is to not buckle and continue to offer a variety of foods.'),(133193904,13386350,'But they\'re up against physiological odds: Children\'s sense of taste is more intense than adults\' because they have more taste buds, priming them to shy away from bitter foods (think Brussels sprouts) and crave sweets. As people age, taste receptor cells are replaced more slowly. '),(133193905,13386350,'Sometime during the elementary school years, children gradually become more adventurous eaters, says                                                                        Laura Jana,                                                                a pediatrician in Omaha, Neb., and co-author of \"Food Fights: Winning the Nutritional Challenges of Parenthood Armed with Insight, Humor and a Bottle of Ketchup.\"'),(133193906,13386350,'Some parents may feel social pressure to raise mini gourmands who appreciate trendy foods: sashimi or Ethiopian injera, for instance. \"In some places, it\'s a badge of honor to have your kids eat exotic foods,\" says Dr. Jana.'),(133193907,13386350,'It can be tough to know when to worry. '),(133193908,13386350,'Dr. Jana, who serves as a spokeswoman for the American Academy of Pediatrics, says a visit to a doctor can reassure a parent that a child isn\'t sick or lacking nutrients.'),(133193909,13386350,'\"If a child is tracking along the predicted rate of growth, they\'re growing absolutely perfectly,\" she says.'),(133193910,13386350,'Parents frequently underestimate how many vitamins and minerals a child consumes. \"Parents will say their kids eat no fruits or veggies except for five things, but those five things may be packed with nutrients,\" says Dr. Jana.'),(133193911,13386350,'A child\'s selectiveness may reflect a food intolerance. Bethany Rabanus sought help after her son, Nicholas, dropped from the 75th percentile in weight at birth to the 10th at his checkup last year at 4 years old. \"It freaked me out,\" says Ms. Rabanus, a physical therapist from Alexandria, Va. \"He would throw tantrums and say \'all I want is crackers or Teddy Grahams.\' If I didn\'t give it to him, he wouldn\'t eat.\"'),(133193912,13386350,'Ms. Rabanus turned to                                                                        Kelly Dorfman,                                                                a licensed nutritionist in North Potomac, Md., and author of \"Cure Your Child with Food,\" who theorized he may be sensitive to gluten, a diagnosis tough to confirm because there is no good test for gluten sensitivity. Ms. Dorfman, who sees about five picky eaters a week, suggested Nicholas cut out gluten and see what happened. '),(133193913,13386350,'\"I was skeptical,\" says Ms. Rabanus. But she was thrilled when Nicholas started gaining weight. \"There is not one thing he won\'t try.\"'),(133193914,13386350,'Teaching good eating habits requires persistence; tastes change, even for adults. Keep offering the same healthy foods but try varying the presentation—if steamed asparagus doesn\'t prove popular, grill it the next time. Introduce new foods with similar consistencies to already accepted ones.'),(133193915,13386350,'Dr. Jana recommends \"no-thank-you bites\" as a way to get children to taste a morsel of food from which they normally recoil. Here\'s how it works: Everyone tries everything. If, after one bite, a child finds the food icky, she may offer up a polite \"no, thank you.\"'),(133193916,13386350,'Proper phrasing can help, Dr. Jana says. \"Instead of, \'If you don\'t finish your pea pods, there\'s no chocolate mousse,\' I say, \'Of course you can have chocolate mousse--as soon as you finish your pea pods.\' \"'),(133193917,13386351,'Kaikki eivät piittaa euroviisuista tuon taivaallista. Mutta jos haluat olla huomenna mukana työpaikkasi kahvipöytäkeskusteluissa, kannattaa väijyä nämä viisi tärppiä.'),(133193918,13386351,'1. Softengine – Something Better'),(133193919,13386351,'Jotain parempaa on tulossa kahdeksantena, kun seinäjokelaisnuoret nousevat lavalle Coldplayn ja Killersin hengessä. Kotisohvalla voi lähteä mukaan ison maailman malliin, ja yhtyä woo-oo-oo –huudatuksiin.'),(133193920,13386351,'2. Meneekö Puola jatkoon rinnan mitalla?'),(133193921,13386351,'Viidentenä esiintyjänä lavalla läträävät pyykkivedellä Puolan Donatan &amp; Cleo. Laulaja, lauluntekijä, maalari Cleo pitää omat rintansa pukunsa suojissa, mutta taustalle on palkattu kaksi puolalaisblondia suurine avuineen.'),(133193922,13386351,'3. Parrakas nainen.'),(133193923,13386351,'Tästä itävaltalaisesta on kohistu pitkin viikkoa. Heti puolalaisten rintojen jälkeen lavalle nousee Conchita Wurst. Sukunimi tarkoittaa makkaraa, ja melkoiseen makkarankuoreen tämä kaunis artisti on myös pukeutunut. Eikä biisikään ole huono. Viisuballadissa on ehtaa James Bond –henkeä.'),(133193924,13386351,'4. Georgian sekametelibiisi'),(133193925,13386351,'IS:n viisutoimittaja nimesi The Shin and Marikon Thre