Will, 4. '),(133194179,13386374,'Owen says on a typical evening, they throw a ball around outside or play board games and action figures indoors. \"Will especially likes to play with blocks,\" he says. He earns about $10 an hour. '),(133194180,13386374,'\"It\'s definitely more enjoyable than physical labor,\" he says. \"I enjoy being around them. They\'re really good kids.\" '),(133194181,13386374,'At Gig Harbor Fire & Medic One, a full-service fire department in Gig Harbor, Wash., Nanette Tatom teaches a baby-sitting class where boys recently made up five of the 12 students—a big change from when she was teaching it 15 years ago and only girls attended, she says.'),(133194182,13386374,'Parents sometimes prod sons to take the class if there are younger siblings at home, she says, or simply because they want them to learn basic safety skills. Another factor is the tight supply of jobs customarily held by teens and young adults, whether in retail, restaurants or recreation. '),(133194183,13386374,'The department uses a curriculum geared to 11- to 14-year-olds and written by Safe Sitter, an Indianapolis nonprofit. It teaches not only about changing diapers, handling tantrums and giving first aid but also about starting a baby-sitting business, interviewing potential clients and figuring out how much to charge. '),(133194184,13386374,'That part usually makes the boys sit up, Ms. Tatom says. Baby sitters in the 11- to 14-year-old range usually can earn from $10 to $15 an hour. '),(133194185,13386374,'The overwhelming majority of baby sitters still are female. Sittercity Inc., a Chicago-based Web service that helps connect parents with sitters, says 95% of its baby sitters are women. '),(133194186,13386374,'UrbanSitter, a San Francisco-based website that matches sitters with families, says its sitters are also overwhelmingly female but its young male sitters have strong followings.'),(133194187,13386374,'Looking at the pool of sitters listed on the site for two years, UrbanSitter found that males had more than twice the number of jobs in 2013 than they had in 2012. Female bookings, by comparison, remained flat.'),(133194188,13386374,'                                                                        Lynn Perkins,                                                                chief executive of UrbanSitter, believes parents generally have become more comfortable with the idea of young men as baby sitters. '),(133194189,13386374,'She thinks a new video feature launched in January, which enables parents to see individual sitters describing their qualifications before hiring, may help male sitters get a second look from families who otherwise would have been reluctant.'),(133194190,13386374,'Tioni Collins, 41, a stay-at-home mother of two \"Star Wars\"-obsessed boys, 7-year-old Aden and 4-year-old Lukas, says the boys get excited about a visit from 17-year-old Ryan Rippetoe. Having a baby sitter who can talk about the Ewoks\' defense strategy on the Forest Moon of Endor is very important, says Ms. Collins, who also lives in Silver Spring, Md. \"It\'s \'Wow, we get to hang out with an older guy,\' \" she says. '),(133194191,13386374,'The way they interact with Ryan is close to how they normally behave, she says. \"They are more naturally inclined to talk about Legos and \'Star Wars\' and cars\" together, Ms. Collins says. '),(133194192,13386374,'Ms. Collins says female baby sitters she has hired seemed less eager to jump in, she says. She pays Ryan the same rate she pays female sitters—$10 an hour.'),(133194193,13386374,'Brooke Randolph, a 33-year old single mom in Indianapolis, says she welcomes a boy baby sitter as a nurturing male presence from time to time for her 7-year-old son, Will. He \"asks for male caregivers,\" she says. \"They play videogames with him. I will not.\" '),(133194194,13386374,'Experts say boy baby sitters are more often hired by families with active boys than by families with girls. That may be due in part to preconceived notions about gender and child care. '),(133194195,13386374,'Deborah L. Best, a psychology professor at Wake Forest University specializing in children and gender issues, says in cultures where many people live close to their extended families, it isn\'t unusual to see young male cousins, siblings and neighbors taking care of young children.'),(133194196,13386374,'Families that aren\'t surrounded by examples of men involved in child care may be fearful of the idea, she says.'),(133194197,13386374,'Four months ago, James Scully, a 22-year-old actor new to New York, signed up on the UrbanSitter website. Baby sitting seemed like a good way to earn extra money between auditions, and he had enjoyed working with children from the ages of 3 to 7 back home in San Antonio. '),(133194198,13386374,'Mr. Scully was surprised at how much harder it was for him to get jobs than it was for his female roommate. \"Many people are resistant to having a young man come into their homes to watch their kids,\" he says. '),(133194199,13386374,'He met Ellen Murphy, a 36-year-old divorced mom in New York City, after her regular baby sitter—Mr. Scully\'s roommate—canceled a job and recommended Mr. Scully as a substitute. '),(133194200,13386374,'Ms. Murphy says she was intrigued, but first paused to think. She had only ever hired female sitters for her 3-year old daughter, Madeline.'),(133194201,13386374,'\"I was a little hesitant,\" she recalls. \"Our culture prescribes that men don\'t have the same instincts as far as taking care of children.\" '),(133194202,13386374,'After an initial phone conversation, she had an in-person meeting with Mr. Scully. \"My daughter took right to him, and I felt extraordinarily comfortable with him there,\" Ms. Murphy says. '),(133194203,13386374,'Mr. Scully did animal impressions, he read \"Ballet Kitty\" to her, they played princesses. \"They had a great time,\" Ms. Murphy says.'),(133194204,13386374,'Now Mr. Scully is her preferred baby sitter. \"I\'m even afraid to send him to the playground with Madeline because I\'m afraid he\'ll get snatched up by another mom,\" Ms. Murphy says. \"I don\'t want to lose him.\"'),(133194205,13386374,' Write to Anne Marie Chaker at anne-marie.chaker@wsj.com '),(133194206,13386375,'Suomi putosi ensimmäiseltä sijalta viidenneksi Pearson-koulutusfirman kansainvälisessä koulutusvertailussa, BBC kertoo. Vertailussa parhaiten pärjäsi Etelä-Korea. Mitalisijat jaettiin Aasian maiden kesken, sillä maailman toiseksi parhain koulutus oli vertailun mukaan Japanissa, kolmanneksi Singaporessa ja neljänneksi Hong Kongissa.'),(133194207,13386375,'Kaksi vuotta sitten Suomen koulutusjärjestelmä arvioitiin samassa vertailussa maailman parhaaksi. Syynä Suomen putoamiseen raportti selittää viimeisimpiä Pisa-tuloksia. Ruotsi sen sijaan putosi kahden vuoden takaiselta 21.sijalta sijalle 24.'),(133194208,13386375,'Vertailu perustuu kansainvälisten testien ja koulutustilastojen yhdistelyyn: tuloksissa on otettu huomiin Pisa-testien lisäksi, miten maat ovat pärjänneet kansainvälisissä matematiikan, luonnontieteiden kokeissa (Timss) ja lukemisessa (Pirls).'),(133194209,13386375,'Myös korkeakoulutulokset ovat vaikuttaneet maiden sijoitukseen, mikä on nostanut Ison-Britannian sijoitusta verrattuna Pisa-testeihin, BBC arvioi. Tässä vertailussa Iso-Britannian koulutus oli kuudenneksi paras, kun Pisa-testeissä maa ei sijoittunut edes 20 parhaan joukkoon.'),(133194210,13386375,'Vertailun toteuttaneen Pearsonin koulutusneuvonantajan Michael Barberin mukaan uusi raportti tarjoaa tähän mennessä syvällisintä tietoa koulutusjärjestelmien kehittymisestä.'),(133194211,13386375,'− Aasian ja Tyynenmeren maiden nousu on ilmiö, jota muut maat eivät voi enää jättää huomiotta. Näiden maiden kulttuurissa tehokas koulutusjärjestelmä yhdistyy kulttuuriin, joka arvostaa kovaa työtä enemmän kuin perittyä fiksuutta, Barber sanoo BBC:lle.'),(133194212,13386375,'Maailman 20 parhainta koulutusjärjestelmää'),(133194213,133863